WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.840
[Unknown]: IVM.

00:00:04.960 --> 00:00:08.880
[Amit Varma]: Before you listen to this episode of the scene in the unseen, I have a recommendation for you.

00:00:08.880 --> 00:00:12.960
[Amit Varma]: Do check out Pulya Bazi, hosted by Saurabh Chandra and Pranay Kotesane,

00:00:12.960 --> 00:00:17.040
[Amit Varma]: two really good friends of mine. Kick-ass podcast in Hindi. It's amazing.

00:00:18.560 --> 00:00:24.000
[Amit Varma]: More than a decade ago, in 2007, I wrote a column with the title The Matunga Racket.

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:28.560
[Amit Varma]: The Matunga Racket was a scam run by the police that a gay friend of mine told me about.

00:00:28.560 --> 00:00:32.960
[Amit Varma]: This was how it functioned. Cops would go to this online messaging board for gay people.

00:00:33.520 --> 00:00:37.840
[Amit Varma]: This was in the days before smartphones and Grindr. A cop would pretend that he was looking

00:00:37.840 --> 00:00:42.640
[Amit Varma]: to hook up. He would lure his victim to Dadar railway station at a particular time.

00:00:42.640 --> 00:00:47.120
[Amit Varma]: A plainclothes cop would complete the rendezvous and be joined by other cops,

00:00:47.120 --> 00:00:51.760
[Amit Varma]: who would then drag their unsuspecting victim, some poor bloke who wanted nothing more than

00:00:51.760 --> 00:00:56.160
[Amit Varma]: a memorable consensual encounter, and take him to King Circle police station. There,

00:00:56.160 --> 00:01:00.720
[Amit Varma]: they would threaten to book him under section 377 of the Indian Penal Code, which effectively

00:01:00.720 --> 00:01:05.680
[Amit Varma]: made homosexual sex illegal. If he was a young man, as he often was, they could even threaten

00:01:05.680 --> 00:01:10.480
[Amit Varma]: to call his parents. Then they would make him empty his pockets, and often they'd take him

00:01:10.480 --> 00:01:15.600
[Amit Varma]: to a nearby ATM, force him to use his ATM card, and take as much as they wanted.

00:01:16.320 --> 00:01:20.800
[Amit Varma]: The point of that column of mine was to talk about the criminalizing of victimless crimes

00:01:20.800 --> 00:01:26.640
[Amit Varma]: with laws like 377, then used by the cops as a tool for extortion. What is the police after all,

00:01:26.640 --> 00:01:32.480
[Amit Varma]: but a legal mafia with a monopoly on violence. Now, since section 377 is no longer on the books,

00:01:32.480 --> 00:01:38.560
[Amit Varma]: you'd imagine that we've solved that particular problem. Not really. Gay people in India may not

00:01:38.560 --> 00:01:44.320
[Amit Varma]: be terrorized by a bad law, but they are still shackled by social attitudes that look upon

00:01:44.320 --> 00:01:50.400
[Amit Varma]: homosexuality as a dangerous aberration, even a disease, and many young people grow up with guilt

00:01:50.400 --> 00:01:55.680
[Amit Varma]: about their secret desires, a guilt that should be as unnecessary as, say, guilt about being left

00:01:55.680 --> 00:02:00.640
[Amit Varma]: handed. Millions of people in our country carry this burden with them every day, this burden of

00:02:00.640 --> 00:02:05.520
[Amit Varma]: shame when there should be no shame, this burden of hiding something about yourself from a family

00:02:05.520 --> 00:02:10.400
[Amit Varma]: that otherwise embraces you as you are. Those born to privilege can find ways of escaping this

00:02:10.400 --> 00:02:16.160
[Amit Varma]: burden. But most gay people in this country, even if they now do not have a law dangling over their

00:02:16.160 --> 00:02:26.400
[Unknown]: heads, still spend their lives in prison. Welcome to the scene and the unseen, our weekly podcast

00:02:26.400 --> 00:02:31.360
[Unknown]: on economics, politics and behavioral science. Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:38.640
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene in the unseen. My guest today is my friend Vivek Tejuja, who has just

00:02:38.640 --> 00:02:43.920
[Amit Varma]: come out with his first book. So now you know, growing up gay in India. This is a charming

00:02:43.920 --> 00:02:49.680
[Amit Varma]: memoir of growing up gay in India. And while it's written in a deceptively breezy, lighthearted way,

00:02:49.680 --> 00:02:54.160
[Amit Varma]: I also found it to be a deeply moving book. Vivek and I have met just a handful of times,

00:02:54.160 --> 00:02:59.280
[Amit Varma]: and our online friendship is actually based on a love of books. Vivek makes his living writing

00:02:59.280 --> 00:03:04.880
[Amit Varma]: about books and his transparent, infectious love for books has often made me rush to Amazon right

00:03:04.880 --> 00:03:10.080
[Amit Varma]: after reading a review or a tweet by him. So some of our conversation today will be about the

00:03:10.080 --> 00:03:14.560
[Amit Varma]: literature and poetry that we enjoy. But much of it will be about the brilliant book that he's just

00:03:14.560 --> 00:03:18.720
[Amit Varma]: written. Before I begin chatting with Vivek, though, let's take a quick commercial break.

