[Amit Varma]: podcast app you happen to prefer. Vivek, welcome to The Seen and the Unseen.

00:04:42.640 --> 00:04:45.920
[Guest]: Hey, hi, Amit. Thanks. Thanks. Happy to be here.

00:04:45.920 --> 00:04:47.920
[Guest]: Tell me a bit about how this book came about.

00:04:48.480 --> 00:04:55.520
[Guest]: So, you know, in 2009, about 10 years ago, I was just working on a couple of chapters. And

00:04:55.520 --> 00:05:02.960
[Guest]: it just started with the memory of which is also there in the book of me and a couple of gay men

00:05:02.960 --> 00:05:10.560
[Guest]: going to Gorai for a trip. And at that time, like you mentioned, it was totally unheard of for

00:05:10.560 --> 00:05:18.720
[Guest]: someone. And I just met one of them once. And I was so taken in by him and his charm. And it was

00:05:18.720 --> 00:05:24.800
[Guest]: not even him that I chatted with online, I chatted with a friend of his that I wasn't interested in.

00:05:24.800 --> 00:05:32.400
[Guest]: And he introduced me to this fellow, Tori, and I absolutely got taken in by him. And I was like,

00:05:32.400 --> 00:05:38.560
[Guest]: okay, you know what, let's do this. Let's go on a trip. And that trip memory, which is in detail in

00:05:38.560 --> 00:05:45.600
[Guest]: the book just evoked the chapter that I first wrote. And then I just started writing chapter

00:05:45.600 --> 00:05:52.560
[Guest]: after chapter. And this was then shelved for 10 years or more. 10 years, yeah, a little less than

00:05:52.560 --> 00:05:58.080
[Guest]: 10 years still. The book was supposed to be a young adult fiction book with another publisher,

00:05:58.800 --> 00:06:05.600
[Guest]: who then decided not to publish it in the memoir form, because they had some objection. And then

00:06:05.600 --> 00:06:11.600
[Guest]: the book went to HarperCollins, my editor Udayan picked it up and he loved it. And that's how this

00:06:11.600 --> 00:06:17.360
[Guest]: book came to be. And that's how I wrote this book. And I added more chapters to those chapters.

00:06:17.360 --> 00:06:23.440
[Guest]: So yeah, and so it's a very short book. So yeah. Yeah, I enjoyed reading it thoroughly. I mean,

00:06:23.440 --> 00:06:29.120
[Amit Varma]: my only criticism, as I told you was that it was too short. It got over when I was just

00:06:29.120 --> 00:06:34.160
[Amit Varma]: settled in. And I thought, okay, a little more of it would have been really nice. Did you always

00:06:34.160 --> 00:06:41.120
[Guest]: kind of want to be a writer or? No, actually, but in a way, it was just one of those very

00:06:41.120 --> 00:06:47.360
[Guest]: lofty dreams that one has, while growing up, when you read other books, and you are so taken in by

00:06:47.360 --> 00:06:51.680
[Guest]: the love of literature that you're like, okay, one day, I'm going to be a writer. So the story

00:06:51.680 --> 00:06:58.400
[Guest]: there is that my father gifted me and he didn't even realize what he was gifting me. I was about

00:06:58.400 --> 00:07:05.600
[Guest]: 14, 15. And he handed me a book called Sisters by Shobha Dey. Okay, I don't know what this is,

00:07:05.600 --> 00:07:10.560
[Guest]: but it just felt close to home, not because of the affluence, but just because they had an Indian

00:07:10.560 --> 00:07:16.560
[Guest]: characters. It had Indian sex, it had everything. And I was like, okay. And then I finished the book

00:07:16.560 --> 00:07:22.080
[Guest]: and at the end of the book I had written, one day I want to be published. You know, I want to write

00:07:22.080 --> 00:07:29.520
[Guest]: and then that's how it came about. And this was way back in 1998-1997. What do you mean Indian

00:07:29.520 --> 00:07:33.680
[Guest]: sex? Sex between Indian characters or something specific? Sex between Indian characters and I

00:07:33.680 --> 00:07:39.840
[Guest]: never read it in a book. Nobody used to write books like these where there was sex between

00:07:39.840 --> 00:07:45.840
[Guest]: two characters and Shobha Dey was all out and I actually enjoyed her after that. I actually read

00:07:45.840 --> 00:07:51.120
[Guest]: all her books. And I was like, why am I reading this shit after a couple of years? But then you

00:07:51.120 --> 00:07:55.200
[Amit Varma]: know what, it's good shit. So I loved it. It's good shit in a sense, she is delightfully

00:07:55.200 --> 00:08:02.720
[Guest]: unpretentious. There are no literary airs or illusions. And I wanted to write in the same

00:08:02.720 --> 00:08:09.360
[Guest]: vein. And that's why this book is so simple. Because it's not. I'm glad that it also ends

00:08:09.360 --> 00:08:18.560
[Amit Varma]: when it ends because I intended it to be short. Let's kind of go to the book and the subject of

00:08:18.560 --> 00:08:25.520
[Amit Varma]: the book and kind of growing up gay. And, you know, I'd done an episode before on this with

00:08:25.520 --> 00:08:29.360
[Amit Varma]: Naveen Nirona, who of course hosts the podcast Keeping it Queer, even you've done an episode

00:08:29.360 --> 00:08:36.400
[Amit Varma]: with him, which we'll link from the show notes. So growing up, I mean, one of the interesting

00:08:36.400 --> 00:08:44.000
[Amit Varma]: things I found about your book was that you were also sort of born to privilege in a sense,

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:50.000
[Amit Varma]: and aware of that privilege. Oh, yes, completely. And how did you know, when did you become aware

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:55.520
[Guest]: of being gay, that there was a difference? I think I was eight. Honestly, I was about

00:08:55.520 --> 00:09:02.960
[Guest]: eight or nine. And I would watch these videos. Or I would watch there would be cassettes brought

00:09:02.960 --> 00:09:08.640
[Guest]: at home of Hindi movies or Bollywood. And I remember watching a movie of Vinod Khanna in it.

00:09:08.640 --> 00:09:15.840
[Guest]: And he was shirtless on the beach in his trunks. And it was Gurbani, I think. And I fell in love

00:09:15.840 --> 00:09:20.400
[Guest]: with what I saw. I fell in lust, actually. I don't know at nine if you can fall in lust.

00:09:20.400 --> 00:09:26.080
[Guest]: But I knew that, you know, I couldn't care about a Zeenat Aman in a bikini. I mean,

00:09:26.080 --> 00:09:32.160
[Guest]: it just didn't matter. And then just incidents and instances kept getting piled on one after

00:09:32.160 --> 00:09:37.440
[Guest]: the other. And while boys in school were talking about girls, I was thinking about other boys,

00:09:38.240 --> 00:09:43.200
[Guest]: pretending to talk about girls. And I was like, Okay, I think I know. I didn't have a term for

00:09:43.200 --> 00:09:49.600
[Guest]: it. I didn't know. It was homosexuality. I didn't know it was being gay. I didn't know any of that.

00:09:49.600 --> 00:09:54.880
[Guest]: I just knew that. Yeah. And I couldn't even ask or tell anyone. So it became a little difficult

00:09:54.880 --> 00:09:59.680
[Amit Varma]: to give a name. Did you feel that? Oh, I mean, what's going on? There's something wrong with me?

00:09:59.680 --> 00:10:04.880
[Guest]: Or? Oh, yeah, completely. Completely. I just wanted to fit to mainstream. Because everywhere

00:10:04.880 --> 00:10:09.120
[Guest]: around you, as you grew up, you see heteronormativity. And that's what I wanted. I

00:10:09.120 --> 00:10:14.880
[Guest]: wanted a wife. I wanted four kids. I wanted a house. I wanted a nine to five job. I wanted

00:10:14.880 --> 00:10:19.040
[Guest]: everything that my father had. Until you saw Vinod Khanna without a shirt. Yeah. And I was like,

00:10:19.040 --> 00:10:24.640
[Guest]: Okay, now I don't think I didn't know whether I wanted him or I wanted the straight life,

00:10:24.640 --> 00:10:30.080
[Guest]: so to say. But but I guess over a period of time, with whatever you go through,

00:10:30.080 --> 00:10:35.120
[Guest]: and whatever you internal conflict, and you just figure along the way that you know,

00:10:35.120 --> 00:10:40.720
[Amit Varma]: this is what you want. And this is what you do not want. It's a kind of an overlap between these two

00:10:40.720 --> 00:10:43.600
[Amit Varma]: phases, like one, because you're looking at your father, and you're looking at all the

00:10:43.600 --> 00:10:46.640
[Amit Varma]: heteronormative stuff. And you're looking at Bollywood romances, and you're thinking,

00:10:46.640 --> 00:10:50.000
[Amit Varma]: Oh, okay, that's the way it's going to go. And then you discover this.

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:57.200
[Guest]: So the only overlap was that, when I discovered and then as I went into my as I entered my teens,

00:10:58.240 --> 00:11:02.560
[Guest]: I just because of the heteronormativity, all I wanted to do was be a woman.

00:11:03.920 --> 00:11:11.040
[Guest]: I equated that there was a man and there's a woman. Right. So while being gay, I never thought

00:11:11.040 --> 00:11:17.360
[Guest]: of it as two men. So at that time, now, of course, things are very different. You're more aware and

00:11:17.360 --> 00:11:23.440
[Guest]: more aware and you read and you interact and you grow with the world, and the people around you.

00:11:24.080 --> 00:11:30.640
[Guest]: But at that time, it was just a dream to be married, even to another man without realizing

00:11:30.640 --> 00:11:34.800
[Guest]: the laws without realizing. So this is the kind of privilege I'm talking about, right? You don't

00:11:34.800 --> 00:11:38.560
[Guest]: was so mollycoddled, you're so cushioned, that you don't realize

00:11:38.560 --> 00:11:40.800
[Guest]: you mentioned in your book, you were the Raja Beta.

00:11:40.800 --> 00:11:46.400
[Guest]: Yeah, yeah, clearly. And, and it was sickening after a point, because then they just invaded

00:11:46.400 --> 00:11:50.800
[Guest]: my life. They wanted to know everything, nothing was hidden, except for this one thing, which was

00:11:50.800 --> 00:11:56.640
[Guest]: hidden for a very long time, till I came out at 18 in frustration, because a man rejected my

00:11:56.640 --> 00:12:02.560
[Guest]: advances or rejected me. And I just didn't know what to do. I was so mad at him that I was like,

00:12:02.560 --> 00:12:05.440
[Guest]: okay, I was angry. And then I decided to come out.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:10.160
[Amit Varma]: You begin your book with an incident which you then allude to later, which is basically you saw

00:12:10.160 --> 00:12:13.760
[Amit Varma]: the film Sarak and you were attracted to the character of Maharani.

00:12:13.760 --> 00:12:19.200
[Amit Varma]: No, I wasn't attracted to the character. But I quite liked what I watched on screen.

00:12:19.200 --> 00:12:24.640
[Amit Varma]: And then you went home and you imitated him and your uncle slapped you. Everybody was,

00:12:24.640 --> 00:12:29.840
[Amit Varma]: and you were stunned by that. And you've written in your book, quote, one incident is all it takes

00:12:29.840 --> 00:12:34.080
[Amit Varma]: for you to not confide in your loved ones, stop quote. And from that point on, it's, it's like,

00:12:34.080 --> 00:12:36.320
[Amit Varma]: it's a secret. You can't even tell your family about it.

00:12:36.320 --> 00:12:37.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's true. Yeah.

00:12:38.240 --> 00:12:42.640
[Amit Varma]: And you also, you know, you write in your book that Bollywood was a sort of a big influence on

00:12:42.640 --> 00:12:46.400
[Amit Varma]: you. It had a big effect on you, which is very interesting, because one is a heteronormativity,

00:12:46.400 --> 00:12:51.600
[Amit Varma]: which you've pointed to that it will show male female relations in a typical cliched way.

00:12:51.600 --> 00:12:55.840
[Amit Varma]: And even there is basically it's not even healthy relationships. A lot of it is just

00:12:55.840 --> 00:13:02.880
[Amit Varma]: toxic masculinity. All of it is very toxic. So it's just that one very toxic prism coming

00:13:02.880 --> 00:13:07.920
[Amit Varma]: through even for women. And the other part of it was how they treat gay characters. So

00:13:07.920 --> 00:13:14.640
[Amit Varma]: how was it for you where your big influences in your life are Bollywood, which is most of the

00:13:14.640 --> 00:13:19.280
[Amit Varma]: popular culture that you're then consuming, and seeing how they treat gay characters after you

00:13:19.280 --> 00:13:20.800
[Guest]: figure out that you're gay yourself?

00:13:20.800 --> 00:13:28.080
[Guest]: Yes, it was very problematic. Because in my head, then I didn't want to be associated with those

00:13:28.080 --> 00:13:32.720
[Guest]: characters, which I've also mentioned in the book, like Pinku from Maskalandar or Maharani

00:13:32.720 --> 00:13:39.600
[Guest]: from Sadak. Or even the way Dostana years and years later, when it came out, I was very,

00:13:39.600 --> 00:13:45.120
[Guest]: very upset with that movie, that how they were depicting. But then I also realized that

00:13:45.120 --> 00:13:51.120
[Guest]: they don't know any better. And how Bollywood played a major role is because in my house,

00:13:51.120 --> 00:13:56.000
[Guest]: there was nothing but screen used to come as a newspaper, as a weekly newspaper then.

00:13:56.000 --> 00:14:03.440
[Guest]: And everybody would just read that. There were only Bollywood magazines, from Stardust to

00:14:03.440 --> 00:14:11.680
[Guest]: Cineblitz to Filmfare and movie and it was just that. That was the consumption. And which is

00:14:12.400 --> 00:14:17.680
[Guest]: until of course, my mother decided to put an end to that. And you know, while that was also going

00:14:17.680 --> 00:14:21.680
[Guest]: on, she decided to involve me more in the world of books and literature. And that's where the

00:14:21.680 --> 00:14:29.360
[Guest]: love began. But I think, and Bollywood upset me for a very long time. But then I decided that

00:14:29.360 --> 00:14:34.560
[Guest]: I also wanted to be a part of the fantastical world. I want to be immersed in that fantasy so

00:14:34.560 --> 00:14:41.200
[Guest]: desperately that you know, I wanted to probably just be with Akshay Kumar when I when I watched

00:14:41.200 --> 00:14:46.720
[Guest]: him shirtless or also there were those other romantic ideas of how Rishi Kapoor was wooing

00:14:46.720 --> 00:14:53.600
[Guest]: Sridevi in Chandni. Or how it was in Lamhe, you know, when you're pining for a lover.

00:14:53.600 --> 00:14:54.880
[Guest]: And you were a big Sridevi fan.

00:14:54.880 --> 00:14:58.720
[Guest]: Oh yeah, completely. Still am. And how you're pining for your lover and how,

00:14:59.280 --> 00:15:03.120
[Guest]: you know, you're longing, I think, I think it was just the feeling of longing.

00:15:03.120 --> 00:15:03.840
[Guest]: The romance.

00:15:03.840 --> 00:15:09.040
[Guest]: The romance, more than the romance, I think the unrequited love, because if one thing that game

00:15:09.040 --> 00:15:14.480
[Guest]: and know most than most men out there is unrequited love. I mean, I could be wrong,

00:15:14.480 --> 00:15:20.240
[Guest]: but from personal experience, I feel is just so looming large or loomed large then.

00:15:21.120 --> 00:15:26.560
[Guest]: But but as you grow, you start seeing things with a different perspective, which helps.

00:15:27.440 --> 00:15:33.200
[Amit Varma]: I mean, what must just thinking aloud what must make that unrequited love a worse problem than it

00:15:33.200 --> 00:15:39.920
[Amit Varma]: is for the toxic in cells who are among the straight men who otherwise roam our countryside

00:15:39.920 --> 00:15:45.040
[Amit Varma]: is that the pool of available choices to you is far less like if I'm a straight person,

00:15:45.040 --> 00:15:51.680
[Amit Varma]: and I see and I'm attracted to a woman, you know, it's something that I can think about

00:15:51.680 --> 00:15:57.280
[Amit Varma]: and consider. And it's fair game if you're both single. But for you, most men are also out of

00:15:57.280 --> 00:16:02.960
[Amit Varma]: bounds. I mean, how do you even is that something that is a I mean, that goes beyond unrequited

00:16:02.960 --> 00:16:10.400
[Guest]: love? It's just, I think maybe that's why we assert our sexuality so much. Like we want

00:16:10.400 --> 00:16:15.440
[Guest]: other men to know at least wanted them to know that we are gay, that we are available,

00:16:15.440 --> 00:16:22.880
[Guest]: that we are single. I mean, the flamboyance and the assertion and the entire drama associated with

00:16:22.880 --> 00:16:33.200
[Guest]: us comes from that latent to be seen, you know, and not to be unseen. To be seen to be visible,

00:16:33.200 --> 00:16:38.480
[Guest]: I think it is so important. Because in your head, how will people know that you're gay?

