00:29:39.920 --> 00:29:43.680
[Guest]: I never made friends in school and college, which was very strange.

00:29:43.680 --> 00:29:46.880
[Guest]: I don't know why. I thought I was popular.

00:29:46.880 --> 00:29:49.920
[Guest]: But of course, I wasn't. Because I was very quiet.

00:29:49.920 --> 00:29:50.880
[Guest]: And I wouldn't mingle.

00:29:51.600 --> 00:29:57.760
[Guest]: And later when I decided that, okay, now it's the time to meet people, to make a friend.

00:29:57.760 --> 00:30:06.240
[Guest]: I think I found people who thought in a similar fashion or who, you know, were there for me.

00:30:06.240 --> 00:30:09.200
[Guest]: And they continue to be there. So yeah.

00:30:09.200 --> 00:30:12.640
[Amit Varma]: So was that sort of initial not making friends or whatever?

00:30:12.640 --> 00:30:16.000
[Amit Varma]: Was it because you were generally a quiet introverted person?

00:30:16.000 --> 00:30:20.320
[Amit Varma]: Or did your own sense of your gayness also have a part to play in it?

00:30:20.320 --> 00:30:24.000
[Guest]: So I think in college, I was very, very inhibited.

00:30:24.000 --> 00:30:27.760
[Guest]: I think it was just, like I said, right, when you can't,

00:30:27.760 --> 00:30:32.720
[Guest]: when you just wait to speak to someone who is like you, and that's not there,

00:30:32.720 --> 00:30:34.320
[Guest]: then you feel a sense of loss.

00:30:35.360 --> 00:30:41.440
[Guest]: I mean, for how long could I just speak with friends who were women and not be able to tell them?

00:30:42.000 --> 00:30:46.160
[Guest]: Like I also mentioned a very close friend of mine, Em, and how she,

00:30:47.200 --> 00:30:51.680
[Guest]: how I fell in love with her, because I was so in denial for the longest time.

00:30:51.680 --> 00:30:54.000
[Guest]: You've written about your yearning to be straight. Yeah.

00:30:54.000 --> 00:30:56.480
[Guest]: And I watched City of Angels with her.

00:30:56.480 --> 00:31:00.000
[Guest]: And then I proposed, for some strange reason, I just proposed.

00:31:00.880 --> 00:31:04.400
[Guest]: And, and then when she found out that I was gay,

00:31:04.400 --> 00:31:07.520
[Guest]: she broke down because she thought that I had a thing for her,

00:31:07.520 --> 00:31:09.680
[Guest]: when though she wasn't really interested.

00:31:09.680 --> 00:31:13.840
[Guest]: So there's a very, very complex situation that played itself out.

00:31:13.840 --> 00:31:16.240
[Guest]: And I don't know why I did what I did, but I did.

00:31:16.240 --> 00:31:19.040
[Guest]: Maybe because we are spending so much time together that I thought

00:31:19.040 --> 00:31:21.920
[Guest]: that I could, you know, veer in that direction.

00:31:22.720 --> 00:31:24.400
[Guest]: And, and that never came to be.

00:31:25.440 --> 00:31:29.200
[Guest]: So, yeah, I mean, I used to look at, I, like I said, right,

00:31:29.200 --> 00:31:32.800
[Guest]: and I keep saying I wanted the straight life because it felt so complete.

00:31:33.760 --> 00:31:37.600
[Guest]: But, but thank God that didn't happen in my life.

00:31:37.600 --> 00:31:40.400
[Guest]: I'm very happy for the, for the lack of it.

00:31:40.400 --> 00:31:46.800
[Amit Varma]: And like a related question that comes up is that because being gay in India is so difficult,

00:31:46.800 --> 00:31:51.680
[Amit Varma]: so difficult, how much does going through that experience, right,

00:31:51.680 --> 00:31:54.960
[Amit Varma]: difficulty rather than being a difficulty in being gay in India,

00:31:56.320 --> 00:32:00.000
[Amit Varma]: go on to define who you are as a person or shape who you are as a person.

00:32:00.000 --> 00:32:03.360
[Amit Varma]: For example, in my case, I know that my sexual orientation

00:32:03.360 --> 00:32:05.360
[Amit Varma]: has absolutely nothing to do with who I am.

00:32:05.360 --> 00:32:05.920
[Unknown]: Yeah.

00:32:05.920 --> 00:32:07.360
[Amit Varma]: You know, it hasn't shaped me in any way.

00:32:07.360 --> 00:32:10.160
[Amit Varma]: I don't have to modify my behavior because of it.

00:32:10.160 --> 00:32:14.240
[Amit Varma]: I don't have to be wary of what I say to people or,

00:32:14.240 --> 00:32:20.160
[Amit Varma]: or, you know, consider carefully the signals that I send out.

00:32:20.720 --> 00:32:24.800
[Amit Varma]: So my orientation hasn't shaped me because I can just take it for granted.

00:32:24.800 --> 00:32:25.920
[Amit Varma]: How has it worked for you?

00:32:25.920 --> 00:32:30.560
[Guest]: So I think my orientation shaped me in a very positive way in the sense that

00:32:31.120 --> 00:32:34.480
[Guest]: the cultural references and the pop culture impact

00:32:35.520 --> 00:32:40.800
[Guest]: or the impact of arts when it came to my life was just something else.

00:32:40.800 --> 00:32:46.800
[Guest]: And when I discovered Giovanni's room, or when I discovered Madonna on MTV,

00:32:46.800 --> 00:32:48.800
[Guest]: and that was a revelation.

00:32:49.520 --> 00:32:51.680
[Guest]: That was, I was like, wow.

00:32:51.680 --> 00:32:52.960
[Guest]: But why a revelation for you?

00:32:52.960 --> 00:32:55.680
[Guest]: Because for me, I'll tell you why.

00:32:55.680 --> 00:33:02.000
[Guest]: Because when I would watch someone like her with such unabashed confidence

00:33:02.000 --> 00:33:06.320
[Guest]: and with such glory in the performance and speaking what she did about,

00:33:06.320 --> 00:33:12.400
[Guest]: which is of sex and love and, you know, being who you are and accepting yourself the way you are,

00:33:12.400 --> 00:33:13.600
[Guest]: that hit a chord.

00:33:13.600 --> 00:33:20.080
[Guest]: And that hit such a strong nerve that you feel that confidence in some way.

00:33:20.080 --> 00:33:23.440
[Guest]: You feel that there's an ally, even though you don't know her,

00:33:24.320 --> 00:33:26.480
[Guest]: and you still know her so well, just like Sridevi.

00:33:27.040 --> 00:33:30.720
[Guest]: You just feel that these people or these celebrities are just allies.

00:33:30.720 --> 00:33:31.520
[Guest]: They are your friends.

00:33:31.520 --> 00:33:35.520
[Guest]: You could perhaps have a conversation with them in your head and be so comfortable about it.

00:33:36.160 --> 00:33:39.680
[Guest]: You know, and the same thing when it came to books, like Tennessee Williams,

00:33:39.680 --> 00:33:43.040
[Guest]: when I discovered A Streetcar Named Desire, or Cat on a Hot Tin Roof,

00:33:43.600 --> 00:33:48.480
[Guest]: or a movie like Gone with the Wind, which was something so empowering about that film,

00:33:48.480 --> 00:33:51.840
[Guest]: even though it has its problems, the book and the movie.

00:33:51.840 --> 00:33:57.840
[Guest]: But just to see Scarlett O'Hara pick a pound of earth in her hand and say,

00:33:57.840 --> 00:34:02.880
[Guest]: I'm never going to go hungry again, instilled something in me that just shook me out of my wits.

00:34:02.880 --> 00:34:05.040
[Guest]: And I was like, you know, it's okay.

00:34:05.040 --> 00:34:08.960
[Guest]: I mean, if these people can do what they are doing and living the life, so can you.

00:34:09.760 --> 00:34:16.560
[Guest]: And that impact on the orientation was so strong that the rest didn't matter, really.

00:34:16.560 --> 00:34:22.560
[Guest]: Like when I first watched Maury's, back then when star movies was the good old star movies.

00:34:22.560 --> 00:34:24.160
[Amit Varma]: Early 90s, I think, yeah.

00:34:24.160 --> 00:34:28.320
[Guest]: And post 1130, they would show movies with a lot of graphic content,

00:34:28.320 --> 00:34:29.360
[Guest]: and a lot of nudity.

00:34:29.360 --> 00:34:33.600
[Guest]: And Maury's was one of them, produced by Merchant Ivory Productions.

00:34:33.600 --> 00:34:35.360
[Guest]: And I fell in love.

00:34:36.000 --> 00:34:40.240
[Guest]: And it wasn't because of the lust, but I think just the fact that this is possible.

00:34:40.240 --> 00:34:44.720
[Guest]: And it spoke to me on so many levels, talking to me about, you know,

00:34:45.600 --> 00:34:50.400
[Guest]: being who you are in a world that probably will take time to accept you.

00:34:50.400 --> 00:34:54.240
[Guest]: And then acceptance didn't become a matter of concern at all.

00:34:54.240 --> 00:34:58.480
[Guest]: It was there, of course, in a very latent manner, it was there.

00:34:58.480 --> 00:35:00.560
[Guest]: But that wasn't the agenda at all.

00:35:00.560 --> 00:35:06.480
[Guest]: The agenda was perhaps just to live and navigate and figure and meet more people like you

00:35:06.480 --> 00:35:12.400
[Guest]: and understand and share stories and figure it out and make your mistakes.

00:35:12.400 --> 00:35:18.560
[Guest]: I have made so many mistakes with the men that I've met, the choices, but it's okay.

00:35:18.560 --> 00:35:21.440
[Amit Varma]: It's been a great journey so far.

00:35:21.440 --> 00:35:25.200
[Amit Varma]: Almost counterintuitive, what you just told me in the sense that you're saying that it kind of

00:35:25.200 --> 00:35:29.760
[Amit Varma]: made you stronger and more comfortable in your own skin, you know, and helped you get past sort

00:35:29.760 --> 00:35:32.800
[Amit Varma]: of the anxieties that humans feel.

00:35:34.160 --> 00:35:37.920
[Amit Varma]: And you mentioned Maury's, so like, what are the sort of early works of art,

00:35:37.920 --> 00:35:42.400
[Amit Varma]: like books or films or whatever, which showed normal gay relationships,

00:35:42.400 --> 00:35:45.840
[Amit Varma]: and not in that whole Bollywood caricature-ish, maskalander kind of thing?

00:35:45.840 --> 00:35:50.800
[Guest]: So I think even, so when, you know, I read this book by Raj Rao called The Boyfriend,

00:35:51.760 --> 00:35:56.240
[Guest]: and The Boyfriend, to me, felt a little maudlin in the sense that,

00:35:57.040 --> 00:36:02.480
[Guest]: again, it spoke about the cruising culture, it spoke about people from different classes

00:36:02.480 --> 00:36:07.520
[Guest]: coming together, and then trying to make sense of what they were feeling towards each other.

00:36:07.520 --> 00:36:12.480
[Guest]: I think the sense of attraction, and the sense of desire was so strong in these works,

00:36:12.480 --> 00:36:18.080
[Guest]: that you start relating on a very different level, like you read books written by

00:36:18.640 --> 00:36:22.640
[Guest]: heterosexual men and women trying to find gay characters in it.

00:36:23.040 --> 00:36:27.120
[Guest]: And you can't, because they are not equipped to perhaps write about it.

00:36:27.760 --> 00:36:31.360
[Guest]: But when you see Gore Vidal's The City and the Pillar, and you then tend to

00:36:32.080 --> 00:36:37.280
[Guest]: find homosexual authors or writers who happened to be gay,

00:36:37.280 --> 00:36:43.920
[Guest]: and you can't ask the librarian in your college, because she'd be mighty scandalized.

00:36:43.920 --> 00:36:45.040
[Guest]: And there's no Google back in the day.

00:36:45.040 --> 00:36:48.240
[Guest]: And there's no Google. So what do you do? You just figure, you just find,

00:36:48.240 --> 00:36:53.600
[Guest]: you read synopsis after synopsis, and try and see that, you know, will you find gay literature?

00:36:54.480 --> 00:36:58.160
[Guest]: Will you find good, solid gay literature to tide you through?

00:36:58.160 --> 00:37:03.120
[Guest]: Like when I thought, when somebody told me, a friend, that a suitable boy has

00:37:03.120 --> 00:37:08.640
[Guest]: some, you know, gay sex, or gay intimacy, I knew I had to read it.

00:37:09.280 --> 00:37:11.680
[Guest]: And that might have been the driving force.

00:37:12.240 --> 00:37:16.880
[Guest]: But of course, ultimately, I loved the book, or that the Golden Gate has a bisexual character.

00:37:18.000 --> 00:37:22.480
[Guest]: So you only want to read because you want to find out that, you know, what it is about me.

00:37:23.200 --> 00:37:29.680
[Guest]: What is it about me that, that makes me different or, or what I don't care about anymore?

00:37:29.680 --> 00:37:34.240
[Guest]: Or I give up caring about because it doesn't make sense anymore.

00:37:35.120 --> 00:37:42.640
[Guest]: So I think these works of art and these books and movies and, and perhaps lives of people,

00:37:43.440 --> 00:37:48.560
[Guest]: just instilled this confidence layer by layer, which had, of course,

00:37:48.560 --> 00:37:51.280
[Guest]: shattered over a period of time because of the bullying and all of that.

00:37:52.000 --> 00:37:55.840
[Guest]: And I was like, okay, let's pick up and see where we go from here.

00:37:55.840 --> 00:38:00.800
[Amit Varma]: No, it's interesting, because I've read and loved a suitable boy many, many, many years,

00:38:00.800 --> 00:38:04.160
[Amit Varma]: I mean, when it came out, basically, and I cannot remember a gay scene, which

00:38:05.200 --> 00:38:08.800
[Guest]: It wasn't a gay scene, it was just intimacy between two characters.

00:38:08.800 --> 00:38:12.320
[Amit Varma]: I can't remember that either. And that's very interesting, because like I recorded an episode

00:38:12.320 --> 00:38:16.160
[Amit Varma]: few weeks back with Ira Mukherjee, which will probably release after this about women in

00:38:16.160 --> 00:38:23.600
[Amit Varma]: history. And she talks about how, when she reads a lot of history, because she her gaze is open to

00:38:23.600 --> 00:38:28.400
[Amit Varma]: it, she will find interesting women characters and interesting things happening to women,

00:38:28.400 --> 00:38:32.000
[Amit Varma]: which men reading the same history simply won't even notice it's like something happening on the

00:38:32.000 --> 00:38:37.120
[Amit Varma]: side. And it's not interesting, but she's looking for it. And so she can see it. And so it's

00:38:37.120 --> 00:38:42.720
[Amit Varma]: interesting that there's that added layer to the way that you're sort of reading this stuff.

00:38:43.280 --> 00:38:49.760
[Guest]: Yeah. So I think I think when you when you want to look for things, they make them

00:38:49.760 --> 00:38:56.400
[Guest]: themselves shown in a way to you that, that perhaps other readers, every reader is different,

00:38:56.400 --> 00:39:01.920
[Guest]: right? So another reader might catch on to something and I might catch on to something else.

00:39:02.720 --> 00:39:03.200
[Amit Varma]: So yeah,

00:39:03.200 --> 00:39:07.520
[Amit Varma]: We'll, we'll talk about books a little later in the show, but sort of going back to

00:39:08.080 --> 00:39:12.240
[Amit Varma]: sort of your growing up years, you know, you've described how it was with school,

00:39:12.240 --> 00:39:16.000
[Amit Varma]: where you're basically you're getting bullied, and you're trying to be unobtrusive. And then

00:39:16.000 --> 00:39:20.960
[Amit Varma]: in college, you gradually open up a little bit, but how was it like at home? Like,

00:39:20.960 --> 00:39:25.280
[Amit Varma]: as far as your family is concerned, you mentioned how, you know, your uncle, for example,

00:39:25.280 --> 00:39:33.760
[Amit Varma]: slapped you once when you did those the dialogues of Maharani and when did they start getting a

00:39:33.760 --> 00:39:35.680
[Guest]: sense of it? And how did they react?

00:39:35.680 --> 00:39:42.720
[Guest]: So I think after that incident, I stopped doing a lot of things. And I've also mentioned in the

00:39:42.720 --> 00:39:48.000
[Guest]: book that growing up in a household of women, for the longest time, I was a part of the kitchen,

00:39:48.000 --> 00:39:54.240
[Guest]: I would go and sit over there. And like I mentioned, listen to songs on the radio with them

00:39:54.240 --> 00:39:58.960
[Guest]: and be a part of them, see how they were cooking, how they were cutting, what was going on in that

00:39:58.960 --> 00:40:04.400
[Guest]: world, how they would gossip. And it was very interesting. I loved just growing up in the

00:40:04.400 --> 00:40:07.840
[Amit Varma]: kitchen. In fact, I'll quote the passage from there, because I kind of liked it. So I,

00:40:07.840 --> 00:40:11.920
[Amit Varma]: I have the book open to that page. Now, before you mentioned the kitchen,

00:40:11.920 --> 00:40:15.920
[Amit Varma]: start quote, I think from there, I learned the art of being the other gender,

00:40:15.920 --> 00:40:21.760
[Amit Varma]: I learned of grace of the subtleties of not expressing everything harshly, or not confining

00:40:21.760 --> 00:40:26.320
[Amit Varma]: oneself to what the world expects of you because you happen to be a man. The songs that would be

00:40:26.320 --> 00:40:30.960
[Amit Varma]: played on the tape recorder in the kitchen would be only by women singers. There was no intrusion

00:40:30.960 --> 00:40:36.320
[Amit Varma]: of male voices in that domain. I was a part of that world till I was about 11 or 12. As soon as

00:40:36.320 --> 00:40:41.680
[Amit Varma]: I turned 13, I knew I wasn't welcome in that space, stop quote. And that's obviously because you're

00:40:41.680 --> 00:40:46.400
[Guest]: deepening of your voice. Yeah, deepening of my voice, also the fact that they understood

00:40:46.400 --> 00:40:53.040
[Guest]: that now he's a teenage boy, his body is growing in ways that they couldn't fathom,

00:40:53.040 --> 00:40:58.560
[Guest]: or they didn't want to, because there's always this distinction in a household. Okay, these are

00:40:58.560 --> 00:41:05.280
[Guest]: the men and you roam with the men when you become a sort of a man. And these are the women and you

00:41:05.280 --> 00:41:11.200
[Guest]: go with and the girls are supposed to become women, when perhaps they have their first period

00:41:11.200 --> 00:41:17.760
[Guest]: or they experience life from there on in the next stage, and so on and so forth. So those very, very

00:41:18.640 --> 00:41:24.640
[Guest]: silly boxing of roles is what took place. And then I just kept quiet. I was like, you know,

00:41:24.640 --> 00:41:31.280
[Guest]: okay, this is what it is. And this is how it will be. Like, you know, even when we used to go to

00:41:31.280 --> 00:41:36.880
[Guest]: watch movies together, the boys and the men would sit separately, the women and the girls would sit

00:41:36.880 --> 00:41:40.960
[Guest]: separately. Yeah, except for of course, just exchanging, okay, what do you want in the

00:41:40.960 --> 00:41:47.040
[Guest]: interview? Shall we get popcorn and so on and so forth. Otherwise, opinions and thoughts weren't

00:41:47.040 --> 00:41:54.320
[Guest]: shared or expressed. So I think that was a big, it was a big lack over there when growing up

00:41:54.320 --> 00:42:01.760
[Guest]: of expression. So I think, when I started expressing myself, out of anger, it was so

00:42:01.760 --> 00:42:06.000
[Guest]: different, because nobody expected that out of me. Everybody thought I was this sort of

00:42:06.000 --> 00:42:13.600
[Guest]: adarsh balak, I would do as told. And they had sort of charted a road map for me that he would

00:42:13.600 --> 00:42:19.760
[Guest]: do this, he would become this and he would have a girlfriend and you'd get him married and so on and

00:42:19.760 --> 00:42:29.520
[Amit Varma]: and so forth. But that never happened. And did this experience also sort of open your eyes to

00:42:29.520 --> 00:42:35.200
[Amit Varma]: the cruelty of men, so to say, in a way that would not otherwise have happened if you weren't gay?

00:42:35.200 --> 00:42:39.920
[Amit Varma]: Like, I think a lot of men like I'm talking not about sort of being straight or being gay here,

00:42:39.920 --> 00:42:45.280
[Amit Varma]: but just in the terms of gender, the cruelty of men is something that is ubiquitous and normalized

00:42:45.280 --> 00:42:50.080
[Amit Varma]: and taken for granted in the way that they treat their women. And just this your sense of identifying

00:42:50.080 --> 00:42:56.720
[Amit Varma]: with the women more of, you know, not understanding why this distinction and why these different roles

00:42:56.720 --> 00:43:02.160
[Amit Varma]: did that open? I mean, did you also then sense that ubiquitous cruelty of men?

00:43:02.160 --> 00:43:08.160
[Guest]: Oh, yeah. From the word go, I mean, men generally that I was surrounded by,

00:43:08.160 --> 00:43:14.320
[Guest]: I expected a certain sort of decorum, so to say, walk this way, you know, chest out,

00:43:14.960 --> 00:43:22.000
[Guest]: shoulders up. Why are you drooping? Why this? Why that? You know, why do you want to wear this?

00:43:22.000 --> 00:43:27.600
[Guest]: Why do you want to talk like this? Deepen your voice and you know, let it be a little gruff

00:43:28.400 --> 00:43:36.800
[Guest]: and abuses, abuses were flying in my house like no one's business. And that's when I realized that,

00:43:36.800 --> 00:43:44.480
[Guest]: you know, for all the books that I read and for everything, I just couldn't communicate anything

00:43:44.480 --> 00:43:50.560
[Guest]: with them because they wouldn't get it. They just wouldn't understand. Like, I couldn't discuss an

00:43:50.560 --> 00:43:55.600
[Guest]: Agatha Christie book, I couldn't discuss Marquez with them. Because in my head, I was way above all

00:43:55.600 --> 00:44:01.040
[Guest]: of this. So in a very flighty sense, also, I was like, these people are just beneath me to discuss

00:44:01.040 --> 00:44:08.880
[Amit Varma]: anything with them, or they won't understand. But did they also read? No, no. And an unrelated

00:44:08.880 --> 00:44:16.160
[Amit Varma]: question before we get back to the family is that, would you feel that people who read more are also

00:44:16.160 --> 00:44:22.480
[Guest]: more empathetic? Not necessarily, not all the time, but most of the time. Yes. I think people

00:44:22.480 --> 00:44:30.480
[Guest]: who read more, I think people who read diversely are more empathetic. People who, like my uncle

00:44:30.480 --> 00:44:35.680
[Guest]: only at some point, he read, but he would only read Alasdair Maclean. I don't know what kind of

00:44:35.680 --> 00:44:42.240
[Guest]: empathy you can get by reading an Alasdair Maclean novel, or a James Hadley Chase novel. But yeah,

00:44:42.240 --> 00:44:45.680
[Guest]: that's what he read. But maybe I guess if you read literature, you'd be... Perhaps,

00:44:46.480 --> 00:44:51.120
[Guest]: I don't want to sound like a literature snob, but yes, why not? We are sounding immensely,

00:44:51.120 --> 00:44:57.600
[Guest]: immensely snobbish. But I think it's fine. It's okay. Because I don't expect them to get it.

00:44:57.600 --> 00:45:04.800
[Guest]: But I think just the idea of not only being gay, but just the fluidity of life, I don't think

00:45:04.800 --> 00:45:11.760
[Guest]: they would, they would get it. It would take a lot of years, and which it has. Which it has. Yeah.

00:45:11.760 --> 00:45:16.720
[Amit Varma]: So tell me about the experience of coming out to your family. Like, how was that? I mean,

00:45:16.720 --> 00:45:23.600
[Guest]: I know it happened in steps. Yeah. I mean, I told my cousin, and she went and blurted it.

00:45:23.600 --> 00:45:29.840
[Guest]: She blurted it? Yeah, to someone in the family. And then I just got all of them together one fine

00:45:29.840 --> 00:45:36.640
[Guest]: day. Everyone. And I just said, Hey, Well, not your parents. My mom, my dad wasn't there around

00:45:36.640 --> 00:45:42.480
[Guest]: at that time. He had gone somewhere and they didn't tell him. Because he had a cardiac problem,

00:45:42.480 --> 00:45:47.120
[Guest]: and they didn't want to shock him, so to say. So I don't know what sort of shock it would be that

00:45:47.120 --> 00:45:51.600
[Guest]: would lead to his death. But but apparently, he knew that's what my mother told me later.

00:45:51.600 --> 00:45:55.920
[Guest]: Yeah. So and when they and when I came out to them, the first thing was, let's go,

00:45:55.920 --> 00:46:02.000
[Guest]: now let's take him to a psychiatrist. And then she showed me some Rorschach paintings,

00:46:02.000 --> 00:46:06.080
[Guest]: and she said, Oh, determine whether he's gay or straight. And I'm like, how can you determine

00:46:06.080 --> 00:46:11.680
[Guest]: that? I'm telling you what I like. I'm telling you who I am. And then she's like, Oh, there's a hint

00:46:11.680 --> 00:46:18.320
[Guest]: of gay. Hint of gay, it's not a color, you know, it's not a hint of purple or hint of orange.

00:46:18.320 --> 00:46:23.760
[Amit Varma]: She's only a little pregnant. Yeah, you can't. How do you how do you define that? And,

00:46:24.880 --> 00:46:30.000
[Guest]: and then she's like, I can, I can be solved with medication. I'm like your Baba Ramdev,

00:46:30.000 --> 00:46:34.880
[Amit Varma]: before Baba Ramdev was Baba Ramdev. Did they try to give you medication? Yeah. Did you take it?

00:46:34.880 --> 00:46:40.800
[Guest]: No. I'm like, this is not going to help anyone. You're fighting a lost cause. I mean,

00:46:40.800 --> 00:46:47.520
[Guest]: I know exactly who I am. And, and that made it even more sure, made me even more sure.

00:46:47.520 --> 00:46:52.080
[Amit Varma]: Now that there was any doubt. But by this time that yearning to be straight had completely gone.

00:46:54.240 --> 00:47:00.800
[Guest]: Now, I just wanted to experience sex. Now, the next level of growing up was just to have

00:47:00.800 --> 00:47:06.400
[Guest]: unbashful sex, just go for it. I mean, and that was very difficult for me initially,

00:47:07.920 --> 00:47:16.240
[Guest]: to engage in that act. Because it just felt very dirty. It, I don't, I never think of it as

00:47:16.240 --> 00:47:23.200
[Guest]: as a very enriching or spiritual experience. I don't know what is so spiritual about sex,

00:47:23.760 --> 00:47:30.400
[Guest]: or having sex, I think it's just very messy. And so that I think this has been instilled,

00:47:31.200 --> 00:47:37.440
[Guest]: because of a certain idea of having early sex when you when you're growing up at 17.

00:47:38.160 --> 00:47:41.600
[Guest]: And then you wonder that, oh, my God, I can't deal with this.

00:47:41.600 --> 00:47:47.920
[Guest]: Hmm. And that's, that's a, that's a, again, a very contradictory statement only because

00:47:49.040 --> 00:47:53.360
[Guest]: primarily in our country, gay people are identified by the amount of sex they have,

00:47:53.360 --> 00:47:57.600
[Guest]: they're meant to be really promiscuous and, and, you know, like sort of

00:47:58.800 --> 00:48:04.560
[Guest]: fawning and falling all over men. And that's when the homophobia steps in.

00:48:04.560 --> 00:48:09.520
[Amit Varma]: No, in fact, I've known homophobic men who almost behave as if being in contact with a gay person

00:48:09.520 --> 00:48:12.160
[Amit Varma]: will mean, you know, the gay guy will try to rape them or whatever.

00:48:15.440 --> 00:48:18.720
[Amit Varma]: And you also mentioned that you've been asked in your book about, you know, how,

00:48:18.720 --> 00:48:20.160
[Amit Varma]: you know, how did you become gay?

00:48:23.280 --> 00:48:30.000
[Guest]: I woke up and I'm like, no, the transformation is the key to life. Let's do this.

00:48:31.840 --> 00:48:36.480
[Guest]: It's a ridiculous question. Till date, I get asked, how was your first time? I'm like,

00:48:36.480 --> 00:48:41.600
[Guest]: well, why do you need to know? I mean, now I can just tell them read the book.

00:48:41.600 --> 00:48:46.240
[Guest]: But yeah, I'm like, buy karo, just buy the book.

00:48:46.240 --> 00:48:49.120
[Amit Varma]: And how did your family react when you had this gathering and you told them?

00:48:50.480 --> 00:48:54.880
[Guest]: First, it was just denial. My mother was like, oh, but you always love Sridevi,

00:48:54.880 --> 00:48:59.600
[Unknown]: you want to marry her and this and that. I'm like, get the hint mom, I always love Sridevi.

00:49:00.960 --> 00:49:05.200
[Guest]: She was one of the and she still is the biggest gay icon there is in the country.

00:49:05.200 --> 00:49:07.680
[Amit Varma]: Oh, I didn't know this. You don't tell her in your book. Why?

00:49:08.560 --> 00:49:15.360
[Guest]: I don't know. I think it's just her zest for life, to put it very, for lack of a better word or

00:49:15.360 --> 00:49:23.760
