01:10:20.880 --> 01:10:24.720
[Amit Varma]: Because when I was growing up, I was surrounded by books. My father had thousands of books.

01:10:24.720 --> 01:10:30.000
[Amit Varma]: And one day at about the age of 10, he had this, I was just looking at a shelf for something

01:10:30.000 --> 01:10:34.000
[Amit Varma]: exciting to read. Up till that point, I had only read, you know, normal things that children of

01:10:34.000 --> 01:10:38.400
[Amit Varma]: that age read. And I came across a book with a very intriguing title, House of the Dead.

01:10:40.560 --> 01:10:43.600
[Guest]: Yeah, no, no, House of the Dead is Dostoevsky. Okay, sorry.

01:10:44.560 --> 01:10:49.280
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, so I thought House of the Dead sounds really exciting. There'll be some adventure

01:10:49.280 --> 01:10:54.640
[Amit Varma]: in it. And I picked it out. And it was an account of Dostoevsky's time in a Siberian prison.

01:10:55.280 --> 01:11:01.040
[Amit Varma]: And I was so hooked that I read all of that. And then I read all of Dostoevsky. And then I,

01:11:01.040 --> 01:11:05.840
[Amit Varma]: for some strange reason, skip to Shakespeare and read all of Shakespeare at age 10. I read

01:11:05.840 --> 01:11:11.920
[Amit Varma]: much more at that age than regrettably I do now. But tell me more about yourself. And in

01:11:11.920 --> 01:11:16.560
[Amit Varma]: your case is also sort of the added angle that for you, it was also a refuge.

01:11:16.560 --> 01:11:23.440
[Guest]: Yeah, yeah, yeah, completely. Like, I remember, I first discovered classics

01:11:23.440 --> 01:11:28.960
[Guest]: through Wuthering Heights. And there was a pocket classic with pictures. And I was like, okay,

01:11:28.960 --> 01:11:34.320
[Guest]: I was about 10, 11. I was like, I was intrigued. I was like, let me just pick this up. It was very,

01:11:35.040 --> 01:11:40.000
[Guest]: it was a big book. And at that time, I didn't know about the concept of unabridged and abridged.

01:11:40.000 --> 01:11:43.760
[Guest]: So I picked it up, and I fell in love with it. It was written very simply,

01:11:43.760 --> 01:11:49.440
[Guest]: because it was, of course, abridged. And I absolutely loved it. I didn't even realize

01:11:49.440 --> 01:11:55.040
[Guest]: it was set in old England and the Moors and everything. I just love the idea of love in that.

01:11:55.040 --> 01:12:01.120
[Guest]: I maybe didn't even realize that it had the ghost element and so much had happened and this and that,

01:12:01.120 --> 01:12:07.680
[Guest]: but just that. I think that there on I started. So then Pride and Prejudice happened.

01:12:07.680 --> 01:12:09.520
[Amit Varma]: And this time, I guess in the unabridged.

01:12:09.520 --> 01:12:16.960
[Guest]: Unabridged. Yes. And for all its flaws, I love Pride and Prejudice. I love Darcy.

01:12:16.960 --> 01:12:22.400
[Guest]: So that was another thing. And when college happened, I think around the same time, my

01:12:22.400 --> 01:12:28.960
[Guest]: exposure to Hollywood, so to say, was with the bodyguard, Kevin Costner and Whitney Houston.

01:12:29.600 --> 01:12:36.560
[Guest]: And I loved Kevin Costner, absolutely charmed by that man. And from there on,

01:12:36.560 --> 01:12:42.240
[Guest]: again, it led to some more literature of a very different kind. Then I started reading a book

01:12:42.240 --> 01:12:48.800
[Guest]: called The English Patient, which I love to date. Like what a book, what a book. And that time,

01:12:49.920 --> 01:12:55.840
[Guest]: Booker, I think I came to know of the Booker because Arundhati Roy won it in 1997,

01:12:56.720 --> 01:13:03.120
[Amit Varma]: when I was 14. An English patient won it the year before. Yes, 1996 or 1995. And that's how I got to

01:13:03.120 --> 01:13:10.480
[Guest]: know of the existence of the English patient. And then I watched the movie. I insisted that my mother

01:13:10.480 --> 01:13:15.760
[Guest]: take me to watch the film. And I fell in love with the movie. And it's one of those very interesting

01:13:15.760 --> 01:13:21.600
[Guest]: instances where the film is also remarkably good. Yes. Which doesn't happen all the time.

01:13:22.160 --> 01:13:28.320
[Guest]: And from there on, from the movie and from the book, I wanted to read Hereditus, because that

01:13:28.320 --> 01:13:34.560
[Guest]: book was mentioned so many times in the movie and the book, The English Patient, you just had to

01:13:34.560 --> 01:13:40.320
[Guest]: read. So you know, I love book references in books. I love that when there's a reading list

01:13:40.320 --> 01:13:46.480
[Guest]: that comes out of a book. When that happens, so that you already have that reading list.

01:13:46.480 --> 01:13:51.360
[Amit Varma]: When I read nonfiction, something I keep doing is I just go to the back very often, I go to the foot

01:13:51.360 --> 01:13:55.280
[Amit Varma]: notes or the end notes very often. So inevitably, if I read a good book, I'll end up reading five

01:13:55.280 --> 01:13:58.720
[Guest]: other books that I picked up because of the end notes. Yeah. Happens to you? Oh, yeah, yeah,

01:13:58.720 --> 01:14:05.440
[Guest]: completely. And when it's fiction, I love when when a character is talking about a book, like

01:14:05.440 --> 01:14:09.600
[Guest]: I just finished reading a book by Ann Patchett, the new one called The Dutch House. And in that

01:14:09.600 --> 01:14:16.080
[Guest]: she's mentioning the Makioka Sisters by Tanezaki. And I love that book. So I'm like, I smile to

01:14:16.080 --> 01:14:22.960
[Guest]: myself and I'm like, hey, there's a camaraderie of sorts between me and the author. You share

01:14:22.960 --> 01:14:28.080
[Guest]: that secret. Yeah, you share that secret book. Or you know that, you know, she also loves it.

01:14:28.720 --> 01:14:34.960
[Guest]: So I think that that is very, very uplifting in the world of books and reading. And when you start

01:14:34.960 --> 01:14:39.280
[Guest]: doing when you when you look out for these red herrings, and you look out for these clues,

01:14:40.160 --> 01:14:44.720
[Guest]: whether it's a sentence or a reference in a TV show, when people talk about books,

01:14:45.440 --> 01:14:50.400
[Guest]: I love that. Like Lost, one of my favorite TV series had so many books mentioned in it.

01:14:50.400 --> 01:14:53.760
[Guest]: So yeah, it just it's just lovely to see that.

01:14:54.800 --> 01:14:56.560
[Amit Varma]: And your mother also read you mentioned?

01:14:56.560 --> 01:14:58.560
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, a lot. A lot.

01:14:58.560 --> 01:14:59.840
[Amit Varma]: So you had books at home?

01:14:59.840 --> 01:15:04.800
[Guest]: I had books at home, I had access to them. And my parents, we had a membership library,

01:15:04.800 --> 01:15:11.040
[Guest]: family membership to British Council. So every weekend, or every week after college,

01:15:11.040 --> 01:15:16.880
[Guest]: I would go to British Library and borrow books. There was I, Claudius, and Claudius the God,

01:15:16.880 --> 01:15:20.400
[Guest]: and Claudius the God, which also had a BBC television series.

01:15:20.400 --> 01:15:22.960
[Amit Varma]: I've seen the I, Claudius BBC television series.

01:15:22.960 --> 01:15:28.880
[Guest]: Yes, it is intense. Oh, yeah, yeah. You know, his grandmother in that show,

01:15:28.880 --> 01:15:35.440
[Amit Varma]: I don't know if you remember, she was so good. But what a character and then what,

01:15:35.440 --> 01:15:41.200
[Guest]: what a book by Robert Graves. I mean, to think that historical fiction was written

01:15:42.000 --> 01:15:44.160
[Guest]: way back. And of course, in a very, very...

01:15:44.160 --> 01:15:47.760
[Amit Varma]: In fact, I never actually read that particular book, I just saw the series. But, you know,

01:15:47.760 --> 01:15:52.160
[Amit Varma]: while we are on that, and we mentioned the English patient, to take a brief digression,

01:15:52.160 --> 01:15:55.120
[Amit Varma]: what are the instances where you have loved both the book and the movie?

01:15:55.680 --> 01:15:58.160
[Amit Varma]: Wow, that's a very difficult question.

01:15:58.160 --> 01:16:03.280
[Amit Varma]: Like my standard answer to that while you think about yours is James Joyce's The Dead,

01:16:03.280 --> 01:16:05.120
[Guest]: which was made into a film by John Huston.

01:16:05.120 --> 01:16:06.640
[Amit Varma]: I'm not, I'm not watched the film.

01:16:07.840 --> 01:16:12.160
[Amit Varma]: It's a lovely film. And remarkably, it's not on your Netflix, Prime and all that it the full

01:16:12.160 --> 01:16:15.680
[Amit Varma]: thing is on YouTube. In a slightly bad print, as they would say.

01:16:15.680 --> 01:16:16.800
[Unknown]: I'll watch it for sure.

01:16:16.800 --> 01:16:20.240
[Amit Varma]: Back in the old days, and I put up a tweet thread on it as well at one point.

01:16:20.240 --> 01:16:24.720
[Amit Varma]: I'm going to look at the show notes. And that was memorably lovely, especially because

01:16:24.720 --> 01:16:28.720
[Amit Varma]: like there is one scene in it, which I love where you've read the story, right?

01:16:28.720 --> 01:16:29.280
[Amit Varma]: Yes.

01:16:29.280 --> 01:16:32.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. So there's one scene where they're leaving the party and

01:16:33.200 --> 01:16:37.280
[Amit Varma]: the male protagonist is at the bottom of the stairs and his wife is coming down. And at one

01:16:37.280 --> 01:16:42.320
[Amit Varma]: point, someone starts singing this song called The Last of Ogrim. And you cut into her face,

01:16:42.320 --> 01:16:47.440
[Amit Varma]: and she has just stopped and he is staring at her riveted. And she is lost in another world.

01:16:47.440 --> 01:16:53.200
[Amit Varma]: And you see that sadness and longing in her face. And she's looking down and Angelica Huston

01:16:54.160 --> 01:16:59.680
[Amit Varma]: just acts beautifully there. And the inside story of that also of that particular scene

01:16:59.680 --> 01:17:04.080
[Amit Varma]: is that this film was John Huston's last film, her father, Angelica's father,

01:17:04.080 --> 01:17:08.240
[Amit Varma]: he was dying, he died before the film was released, but after it was made.

01:17:08.240 --> 01:17:12.720
[Amit Varma]: So when she looked down from the stairs, she saw him on a wheelchair with oxygen pipes.

01:17:12.720 --> 01:17:13.920
[Amit Varma]: Oh, that's why the sadness.

01:17:13.920 --> 01:17:17.520
[Amit Varma]: And that's where the sadness came from. And it's a mind blowing scene. And of course,

01:17:17.520 --> 01:17:21.680
[Amit Varma]: the scene itself alone is on YouTube. But that's that's one book.

01:17:21.680 --> 01:17:25.280
[Guest]: But I must tell you, sorry to interrupt, but there's this one other story to

01:17:25.840 --> 01:17:32.640
[Guest]: The Last of Ogrim is that James and his wife Nora used to share the song.

01:17:32.640 --> 01:17:32.960
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:17:32.960 --> 01:17:35.680
[Guest]: And they loved this song. And it was part of their song,

01:17:36.240 --> 01:17:42.080
[Guest]: right from their marriage to their death, one of the deaths or so. So yeah, that's the story to

01:17:42.080 --> 01:17:45.840
[Guest]: that. I mean, there's a movie called Nora, which is based on

01:17:45.840 --> 01:17:50.400
[Guest]: Which has a beautiful scene where Susan Lynch is singing this song with

01:17:50.400 --> 01:17:52.080
[Guest]: Even Juan McGregor.

01:17:52.080 --> 01:17:52.880
[Guest]: Yeah, and he's playing

01:17:52.880 --> 01:17:56.800
[Guest]: Which is beautiful. I mean, and that also I saw, courtesy British Library.

01:17:56.800 --> 01:18:01.680
[Amit Varma]: And the interesting thing is that that incident, the Michael Fury incident was inspired by

01:18:01.680 --> 01:18:03.120
[Amit Varma]: something which actually happened to Nora.

01:18:03.120 --> 01:18:03.360
[Guest]: Yes.

01:18:03.360 --> 01:18:04.560
[Guest]: There was a Michael Fury in her life.

01:18:04.560 --> 01:18:05.120
[Guest]: Yes.

01:18:05.120 --> 01:18:07.120
[Guest]: And which I hadn't known till recently.

01:18:07.120 --> 01:18:14.480
[Guest]: Yeah, because I read the biography of Nora Joyce by a lady called Brenda Wex or something

01:18:14.480 --> 01:18:20.240
[Unknown]: to that effect. But what a biography. You must pick it up if you ever get a chance.

01:18:20.240 --> 01:18:21.360
[Amit Varma]: Sorry, books to movies.

01:18:21.360 --> 01:18:22.080
[Guest]: Books to movies.

01:18:22.640 --> 01:18:23.920
[Amit Varma]: Yes, you were saying.

01:18:24.640 --> 01:18:27.120
[Amit Varma]: You were saying I'm done. I wanted to just jog.

01:18:27.120 --> 01:18:32.800
[Guest]: I love Gone with the Wind. I think, like I said, people may find it problematic today.

01:18:32.800 --> 01:18:38.560
[Guest]: But going by the time it was made and how it was made. I absolutely loved it.

01:18:38.560 --> 01:18:42.960
[Guest]: Though at that time also, it was problematic in the sense that Clark, there was another actor

01:18:42.960 --> 01:18:50.560
[Guest]: supposed to play the role of Fred Butler, but was replaced because he was known to be a homosexual.

01:18:50.560 --> 01:18:53.920
[Guest]: I can't remember the name of the actor. And the director just didn't want that.

01:18:53.920 --> 01:18:54.480
[Guest]: Who was this?

01:18:54.480 --> 01:18:58.240
[Amit Varma]: I can't remember. But there's a story you can google it.

01:18:58.240 --> 01:18:59.200
[Amit Varma]: You can google it.

01:18:59.200 --> 01:19:05.840
[Guest]: And how they then got Clark Gable to play Fred Butler, which was really sad.

01:19:05.840 --> 01:19:08.720
[Guest]: Clark Gable benefiting from the homophobia of others.

01:19:08.720 --> 01:19:14.560
[Guest]: There you go, of Hollywood. So that was that. I love The Postman Always Rings Twice by James

01:19:14.560 --> 01:19:20.400
[Guest]: M. Cain. And I love the movie also, only because of John Garfield. Absolutely find him so stunningly

01:19:20.400 --> 01:19:25.600
[Guest]: hot. I was like, I was just glued to Turner classic movies at one time in my life. I mentioned

01:19:25.600 --> 01:19:31.760
[Guest]: in the book as well. And Cat on a Hot Tin Roof with Paul Newman, looking the way he did.

01:19:33.680 --> 01:19:37.760
[Guest]: And the play by Tennessee Williams, which I again love, because Tennessee Williams,

01:19:37.760 --> 01:19:45.680
[Guest]: this latent homosexuality in all his plays, does a wonderful job of projecting that into either his

01:19:45.680 --> 01:19:52.960
[Guest]: women or his men, but mostly women. His angst and everything comes out through the women characters,

01:19:52.960 --> 01:19:56.160
[Guest]: which I think is a brilliant job that he did as a playwright.

01:19:56.160 --> 01:20:00.560
[Amit Varma]: You know, I read him when I was a teenager, like decades ago. So I've probably got to reread

01:20:00.560 --> 01:20:04.400
[Amit Varma]: him in that light. I mean, another great translation of story to film I thought was

01:20:04.400 --> 01:20:05.360
[Amit Varma]: Brokeback Mountain.

01:20:05.360 --> 01:20:06.080
[Guest]: I love that.

01:20:06.880 --> 01:20:09.920
[Amit Varma]: The story, of course, came out in, I think, 98 or 99 in New York.

01:20:10.640 --> 01:20:12.080
[Guest]: Annie Proulx, I don't know.

01:20:12.080 --> 01:20:13.520
[Guest]: Annie Proulx, yeah, neither do I.

01:20:13.520 --> 01:20:15.120
[Guest]: Yeah, but what a story.

01:20:15.120 --> 01:20:17.520
[Amit Varma]: And have you seen that film called In the Bedroom?

01:20:18.080 --> 01:20:18.800
[Amit Varma]: No.

01:20:18.800 --> 01:20:22.640
[Amit Varma]: Okay, In the Bedroom is based on a short story by Andre Dubu.

01:20:22.640 --> 01:20:26.960
[Guest]: I think that's how you pronounce it. Dubu is just a glorious, glorious short story.

01:20:26.960 --> 01:20:30.720
[Amit Varma]: And the story was called something else. I think it came in either New York or Paris

01:20:30.720 --> 01:20:37.280
[Amit Varma]: Review or one of these. And the story basically is about these parents whose son is killed by

01:20:37.280 --> 01:20:42.000
[Amit Varma]: someone and then they want to take revenge. Son is killed in the sense, maybe it's an accident.

01:20:42.000 --> 01:20:46.480
[Amit Varma]: I don't even remember now. But it's a very nice short story. And it's a beautiful film.

01:20:47.280 --> 01:20:50.880
[Amit Varma]: Classic film, one of my favorites, but they're very different from each other,

01:20:50.880 --> 01:20:57.680
[Amit Varma]: which is also sort of very interesting on how you take a story which is much more compressed.

01:20:57.680 --> 01:21:01.200
[Guest]: And then you just build this dramatic thing out of it.

01:21:01.200 --> 01:21:06.400
[Guest]: Which is great because I love him as a short story writer. And I wish there were more,

01:21:06.400 --> 01:21:14.320
[Guest]: more, you know, movies based on books in India. I've seen so many. I love Gumna

01:21:16.320 --> 01:21:22.320
[Guest]: based on And Then There Were None. I love because it's so bad. It's so hammy that I love it.

01:21:22.320 --> 01:21:27.920
[Guest]: Like for the longest time, when I got my tribe of gay men as friends and all of that,

01:21:27.920 --> 01:21:32.960
[Guest]: we would play the song that Helen dances to in that movie Kitty Kelly on the beach,

01:21:32.960 --> 01:21:37.680
[Guest]: and we would dance to it as well at a friend's house, because it was so funny,

01:21:37.680 --> 01:21:44.880
[Guest]: the song and the way it was done. And then we used to copy steps of the song and it was very

01:21:44.880 --> 01:21:50.320
[Guest]: interesting. So I think Indian literature has a lot. I mean, I love Devdas for all its,

01:21:50.880 --> 01:21:56.320
[Guest]: again, such a badly made movie by Bansali. It's a horrendously bad film. It's a horrendously bad

01:21:56.320 --> 01:22:00.240
[Guest]: film. But I just love it. I don't know why because of Madhuri and Aishwarya, I guess.

01:22:00.240 --> 01:22:06.480
[Guest]: But I love some, I love their interaction in the film. I don't like the book at all. But yeah.

01:22:07.440 --> 01:22:13.280
[Amit Varma]: This is a completely, by the way, diversion. But my father once used to be director of the

01:22:13.280 --> 01:22:18.800
[Amit Varma]: Film and Television Institute of India in the late 80s. And he expelled Sanjay Leela Bansali.

01:22:18.800 --> 01:22:20.000
[Guest]: Excellent. Good choice.

01:22:20.000 --> 01:22:25.200
[Amit Varma]: Not for the right reasons. It was, I think, more to do with misbehavior. But I would have expelled

01:22:25.200 --> 01:22:30.320
[Guest]: him for aesthetic reasons. You know, there's this one movie that I don't know if you watched it,

01:22:30.320 --> 01:22:39.760
[Guest]: based on Madame Bovary by Flaubert. I really enjoyed the film. I love the book. But I enjoyed

01:22:39.760 --> 01:22:46.800
[Guest]: the film because I thought Deepa Saini did such a good job. And it was a Doordarshan film. I think,

01:22:46.800 --> 01:22:52.640
[Guest]: yeah. So that I really liked. And a lot of movies that time on Doordarshan that were made

01:22:52.640 --> 01:22:58.400
[Guest]: were from books like Party, right? By Mahesh, I can't pronounce his last name.

01:22:58.400 --> 01:22:59.040
[Unknown]: Elkunchwar.

01:22:59.040 --> 01:23:03.440
[Unknown]: Elkunchwar, yeah. Party is Mahesh.

01:23:03.440 --> 01:23:05.440
[Guest]: I think he wrote the play and Govind Nilani made the film.

01:23:05.440 --> 01:23:06.800
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, Govind Nilani made the film.

01:23:06.800 --> 01:23:10.640
[Amit Varma]: By the way, I don't think I've told you this. But since you had mentioned before we recorded that

01:23:10.640 --> 01:23:16.160
[Amit Varma]: you had liked the book I released 10 years ago. That was almost made into a film by Govind Nilani.

01:23:16.160 --> 01:23:20.560
[Amit Varma]: In the sense, he got in touch with me and he said, I'd like to make the film. And I even worked on a

01:23:20.560 --> 01:23:26.720
[Amit Varma]: script treatment for him, but he could never raise funding for it. At which point he said that Marathi

01:23:26.720 --> 01:23:32.000
[Amit Varma]: film industry is like, Hindi film industry was in the early 80s, and he still couldn't get funding.

01:23:32.000 --> 01:23:37.040
[Amit Varma]: And I was kind of flabbergasted that a guy of his stature who's made the kind of movies he has

01:23:37.040 --> 01:23:39.200
[Guest]: is not being able to fund it. It's crazy.

01:23:39.200 --> 01:23:42.160
[Guest]: Maybe you want to pitch it to Netflix?

01:23:42.160 --> 01:23:44.480
[Amit Varma]: No, I don't want to pitch it at all. It was a terrible book. I don't know.

01:23:44.480 --> 01:23:50.640
[Guest]: It wasn't, not at all, please. Now you're just fishing.

01:23:50.640 --> 01:23:54.880
[Amit Varma]: No, and I have an interesting Mayam Aimsaab story also. So I was in college when I was

01:23:54.880 --> 01:24:00.960
[Amit Varma]: a hostelite in Ferguson College, Pune when Mayam Aimsaab was released. And if any of my

01:24:00.960 --> 01:24:05.200
[Amit Varma]: hostel mates are listening to this, I, after all these years, I apologize for what I did.

01:24:05.200 --> 01:24:09.360
[Amit Varma]: So what I did was I went and watched the first day first show. And then I went back to the

01:24:09.360 --> 01:24:14.240
[Amit Varma]: hostel and I gathered everyone around and I described in detail a number of lurid scenes,

01:24:14.240 --> 01:24:19.200
[Amit Varma]: which were not in the film. Right. So then all of them go to watch first day third show.

01:24:19.200 --> 01:24:20.080
[Amit Varma]: And they're disappointed.

01:24:20.080 --> 01:24:27.040
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And then they come back out saying, Amit, the censors cut it for the third show.

01:24:27.040 --> 01:24:37.520
[Guest]: No, so I got to watch the uncensored version through a library VHS tape. And even then,

01:24:37.520 --> 01:24:41.600
[Guest]: I mean, Shah Rukh did nothing for me, but I just liked the way the movie was,

01:24:41.600 --> 01:24:47.120
[Guest]: except for the horrendous Raj Babbar in it. Like, why is he there in the film? But,

01:24:48.080 --> 01:24:51.200
[Guest]: but yeah, it was a good movie. I quite enjoyed it.

01:24:51.200 --> 01:24:57.280
[Amit Varma]: I kind of felt it was a little bit of a sort of random movie.

01:24:57.280 --> 01:25:00.480
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, very, very self indulgent, no doubt.

01:25:00.480 --> 01:25:04.000
[Amit Varma]: Let us now take a poem break. I think both of us have got about three,

01:25:04.000 --> 01:25:08.400
[Guest]: four poems that we are happy to talk about and read. Let's begin with you.

01:25:08.400 --> 01:25:14.720
[Guest]: Okay, so this is one of my favorite poems, one of my favorite people, Eunice, Eunice D'Souza.

01:25:15.360 --> 01:25:23.840
[Guest]: The poem is advice to women. And very strangely, this always reminds me of 36 Chaurangi Lane,

01:25:23.840 --> 01:25:28.160
[Guest]: which I love. And I wish somebody would write a book out of that movie. That's

01:25:29.120 --> 01:25:35.680
[Guest]: a movie that I want to read. One of my all time favorite films. So I think that's also got to do

01:25:35.680 --> 01:25:44.160
[Guest]: with the idea of gay man aging, old alone, which is very scary. We'll talk about that some other

01:25:44.160 --> 01:25:50.400
[Guest]: time. But here's a poem called advice to women. Keep cats if you want to learn to cope with the

01:25:50.400 --> 01:25:57.520
[Guest]: otherness of lovers. Otherness is not always neglect. Cats return to their litter trays

01:25:57.520 --> 01:26:04.560
[Guest]: when they need to. Don't cuss out of the window at their enemies. That stare of perpetual surprise

01:26:04.560 --> 01:26:08.560
[Guest]: in those great green eyes will teach you to die alone.

01:26:09.600 --> 01:26:15.040
[Amit Varma]: Lovely. And I love all this stuff. And it's very interesting. I mean, how do you feel about this,

01:26:15.040 --> 01:26:22.080
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, I feel very awkward reading poetry aloud or listening to spoken poetry,

01:26:22.080 --> 01:26:26.000
[Amit Varma]: in fact, because, you know, it seems to me that I read it one way in a page.

01:26:26.000 --> 01:26:30.880
[Amit Varma]: And then when you hear it, it's a completely different beast. Even though the sound matters

01:26:30.880 --> 01:26:35.520
[Amit Varma]: so much. But so you know, these poetry readings just seem to me like, what?

01:26:35.520 --> 01:26:41.040
[Guest]: I think they are very pretentious. And there are a lot of them today,

01:26:42.080 --> 01:26:47.520
[Guest]: spoken word performances and all, which is, see, I'm not taking away from the beauty of the poem.

01:26:47.520 --> 01:26:53.840
[Guest]: But just by being read aloud, I don't know. I think the entire drama and performance attached

01:26:53.840 --> 01:27:00.400
[Guest]: to it. So that's something that maybe I don't know how I'll react to in person when this happens.

01:27:00.400 --> 01:27:06.720
[Guest]: So I don't attend them anyway. But it's fun to know that there are voices, it's good to know that

01:27:06.720 --> 01:27:11.120
[Guest]: there are so many voices that are emerging or emerge because of this practice.

01:27:11.120 --> 01:27:16.160
[Amit Varma]: And as a sort of a book critic, do you also find expectations of what a critic must do,

01:27:16.160 --> 01:27:20.160
[Amit Varma]: especially from the more academic sorts, that the critics have to have a particular way of

01:27:20.160 --> 01:27:23.040
[Amit Varma]: doing their criticism? I'm not a critic.

01:27:23.040 --> 01:27:23.920
[Guest]: But you write about books.

01:27:23.920 --> 01:27:30.880
[Guest]: I write about books, but I don't care what people have to say. Because people say a lot of things of

01:27:30.880 --> 01:27:38.640
[Guest]: how things should be written about or viewed or said or listened to. But I think it's okay. I mean,

01:27:39.600 --> 01:27:44.000
[Guest]: you can't make them all happy, right? So why bother? Your poem?

01:27:44.880 --> 01:27:49.120
[Amit Varma]: Okay, let me read out something. Have you read Mark Strand?

01:27:49.120 --> 01:27:54.880
[Guest]: Yes. You had mentioned it online, I remember on Twitter, and I replied to you as well.

01:27:55.520 --> 01:27:57.120
[Amit Varma]: Saying how much I love Mark Strand.

01:27:57.120 --> 01:28:01.760
[Amit Varma]: I love Mark Strand. In particular, I like his later work. His last book of poems before he

01:28:01.760 --> 01:28:07.280
[Amit Varma]: died was called Almost Invisible. And it's a book of prose poems. So if someone who is not into that

01:28:07.280 --> 01:28:12.240
[Amit Varma]: stuff looks at it, they'll just see one paragraph and they'll say, how is this poem? But and even

01:28:12.240 --> 01:28:14.640
[Amit Varma]: I can't really answer that question. Can you?

01:28:14.640 --> 01:28:22.560
[Guest]: No, Anne Carson does a beautiful job of prose poetry. A lot of people do that.

01:28:23.280 --> 01:28:24.240
[Guest]: A prose poetry.

01:28:25.520 --> 01:28:29.440
[Amit Varma]: Mark Strand's book is pretty spectacular. So the first poem I'll read out is actually a prose poem.

01:28:29.440 --> 01:28:35.200
[Amit Varma]: It's called You Can Always Get There From Here. And in a sense, you know, this poem before I read

01:28:35.200 --> 01:28:40.160
[Amit Varma]: it out, in a sense, this is a little poignant, because it feels to me that this might be a

01:28:40.160 --> 01:28:46.000
[Amit Varma]: direction in which we might be going in India. You know, the overall sense of it. And that's,

01:28:46.000 --> 01:28:47.680
[Amit Varma]: but maybe that's just my take.

01:28:47.680 --> 01:28:50.080
[Amit Varma]: You Can Always Get There From Here by Mark Strand.

01:28:50.640 --> 01:28:54.560
[Amit Varma]: A traveler returned to the country from where he had started many years before.

01:28:54.560 --> 01:28:58.560
[Amit Varma]: When he stepped from the boat, he noticed how different everything was.

01:28:58.560 --> 01:29:02.960
[Amit Varma]: There were once many buildings, but now there were few and each of them needed repair.

01:29:03.520 --> 01:29:05.600
[Amit Varma]: In the park where he played as a child,

01:29:05.600 --> 01:29:10.400
[Amit Varma]: dust filled shafts of sunlight struck the tawny leaves of trees and withered hedges.

01:29:10.400 --> 01:29:14.000
[Amit Varma]: Empty trash bags littered the grass. The air was heavy.

01:29:14.000 --> 01:29:19.040
[Amit Varma]: He sat on one of the benches and explained to the woman next to him that he'd been away a long time,

01:29:19.040 --> 01:29:21.440
[Amit Varma]: then asked her what season had he come back to.

01:29:22.000 --> 01:29:26.000
[Amit Varma]: She replied that it was the only one left, the one they had all agreed on.

01:29:27.120 --> 01:29:32.240
[Amit Varma]: And in this poem, I don't mean literally that India is going to look like the Soviet dystopian

01:29:32.240 --> 01:29:32.560
[Guest]: thing.

01:29:32.560 --> 01:29:38.640
[Guest]: The imagery is so powerful when you're talking about the sunlight or you're talking about

01:29:39.600 --> 01:29:43.520
[Guest]: the leaves and the hedges and you're talking about how he steps out of that.

01:29:44.160 --> 01:29:48.000
[Amit Varma]: And I don't mean this literal sense of decay or everything looks the same or whatever,

01:29:48.000 --> 01:29:51.680
[Amit Varma]: but just a sense that this is a season that everyone has agreed upon.

01:29:51.680 --> 01:29:53.920
[Amit Varma]: And you kind of, you know,

01:29:53.920 --> 01:29:54.960
[Guest]: The season of loss.

01:29:56.480 --> 01:29:59.440
[Amit Varma]: I think he might well have had the Soviet Union in mind, for example,

01:29:59.440 --> 01:30:03.440
[Guest]: when he wrote this, which was pretty much where it was, you had a totalitarian regime

01:30:04.160 --> 01:30:06.000
[Guest]: insisting on its own vision of the world.

01:30:06.000 --> 01:30:07.200
[Guest]: We are not very far from it.

01:30:07.760 --> 01:30:09.760
[Amit Varma]: But that's, well, I mean,

01:30:09.760 --> 01:30:11.840
[Amit Varma]: Scary, but yeah, well.

01:30:12.960 --> 01:30:18.960
[Amit Varma]: That's kind of, so do you ever get snobbery from book people that, you know, why do you like this?

01:30:18.960 --> 01:30:23.120
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, are there writers who are supposed to be cool to read and not so cool to read?

01:30:23.120 --> 01:30:27.280
[Amit Varma]: Like you mentioned earlier in the episode that you had liked Shobhadeh's sisters.

01:30:27.280 --> 01:30:29.680
[Amit Varma]: But that, of course, was when you were first given it.

01:30:29.680 --> 01:30:31.760
[Unknown]: And that's not necessarily what you like today.

01:30:31.760 --> 01:30:32.240
[Unknown]: Yeah.

01:30:32.240 --> 01:30:36.720
[Amit Varma]: But is there somehow that, I mean, you know, I, for example,

01:30:36.720 --> 01:30:39.680
[Amit Varma]: I discovered Haruki Murakami in the late 90s.

01:30:39.680 --> 01:30:42.640
[Amit Varma]: I think when I read him in Playboy, of all things, I read Playboy for the stories.

01:30:42.640 --> 01:30:45.120
[Guest]: Yeah, there were some fantastic stories right there.

01:30:45.120 --> 01:30:45.440
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:30:45.440 --> 01:30:46.960
[Amit Varma]: And I was a fan of Murakami from then.

01:30:46.960 --> 01:30:50.240
[Amit Varma]: And it was kind of disconcerting that about a decade or a decade and a half ago,

01:30:50.240 --> 01:30:53.600
[Amit Varma]: it suddenly became cool to like Murakami when the rest of the world caught on.

01:30:53.600 --> 01:30:54.400
[Amit Varma]: And now to hate it.

01:30:55.440 --> 01:30:56.880
[Guest]: And now to hate it.

01:30:56.880 --> 01:31:00.320
[Guest]: Like I discovered him in 2001 with Sputnik Sweetheart.

01:31:00.320 --> 01:31:00.800
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:31:00.800 --> 01:31:02.800
[Guest]: And that was the time I lost my father.

01:31:02.800 --> 01:31:05.200
[Guest]: So that book has always been very special.

01:31:05.200 --> 01:31:10.640
[Guest]: You know, it's somehow, it's not the loss of my dad that would make me stop reading that book.

01:31:10.640 --> 01:31:11.840
[Unknown]: In fact, I read it every year.

01:31:12.400 --> 01:31:14.320
[Guest]: I love that book so much.

01:31:14.320 --> 01:31:16.800
[Guest]: There's something maybe because it speaks of loss.

01:31:17.440 --> 01:31:21.280
[Guest]: And it speaks of, again, love not being found.

01:31:21.280 --> 01:31:26.080
[Guest]: So I think it just connected at a very, very deeper level.

01:31:26.080 --> 01:31:31.120
[Guest]: But I get what you mean about authors being dissed and being loved later.

01:31:31.120 --> 01:31:34.400
[Guest]: And then you're like, I have been reading him, you discovered him right now.

01:31:34.400 --> 01:31:35.760
[Guest]: So you shut up kind of a thing.

01:31:37.600 --> 01:31:40.640
[Guest]: That kind of book snobbery is there in my head.

01:31:40.640 --> 01:31:42.080
[Guest]: I don't say it out loud.

01:31:42.080 --> 01:31:43.600
[Guest]: But now I have said it out loud.

01:31:45.120 --> 01:31:46.240
[Guest]: So sometimes it's there.

01:31:46.800 --> 01:31:49.200
[Guest]: I'm like, why can't you get what the author is trying to tell you?

01:31:49.200 --> 01:31:53.360
[Guest]: But then I also see that there are different things that people take from the same book.

01:31:53.360 --> 01:31:57.840
[Amit Varma]: And then also you see people making that effort because it's cool to like Murakami.

01:31:57.840 --> 01:32:02.240
[Amit Varma]: You buy Murakami and you read him and you're making the effort to like Murakami to be cool

01:32:02.240 --> 01:32:05.840
[Amit Varma]: rather than just take joy in the book itself as the case may be.

01:32:05.840 --> 01:32:10.640
[Guest]: I mean, the short story of his I read, in fact, was one called The Second Bakery Attack.

01:32:10.640 --> 01:32:12.560
[Guest]: Yes, it was in The Elephant Vanishes.

01:32:12.560 --> 01:32:13.680
[Guest]: It was in The Elephant Vanishes.

01:32:13.680 --> 01:32:18.320
[Amit Varma]: Yes, it had come second or third story in The Elephant Vanishes, a beautiful story.

01:32:18.320 --> 01:32:19.040
[Amit Varma]: Lovely story.

01:32:19.040 --> 01:32:23.440
[Guest]: One of my favorite Murakami stories is in After the Quake.

01:32:24.160 --> 01:32:25.520
[Guest]: I don't know if you've read it.

01:32:25.520 --> 01:32:26.720
[Unknown]: I've read it but I may not remember.

01:32:26.720 --> 01:32:32.640
[Guest]: There's a last story called, I can't remember what it's called, Honey something, Honey Bun

01:32:33.520 --> 01:32:40.560
[Guest]: or something to that effect about a girl and her single mother and a friend who loves the

01:32:41.120 --> 01:32:46.800
[Guest]: girl's mother and how they make this strange family unit beautifully written.

01:32:46.800 --> 01:32:55.760
[Guest]: One of his more life-affirming stories and not so pessimistic, but a great one.

01:32:56.480 --> 01:32:58.800
[Amit Varma]: I've got to kind of revisit that.

01:32:58.800 --> 01:33:02.800
[Amit Varma]: Speaking of stories for a moment, like another writer I've loved for many, many years and

01:33:02.800 --> 01:33:03.840
[Amit Varma]: we've actually discussed her.

01:33:03.840 --> 01:33:06.240
[Amit Varma]: So I know you love her also, Alice Munro.

01:33:06.240 --> 01:33:07.200
[Amit Varma]: Yes, oh my God.

01:33:07.200 --> 01:33:10.720
[Amit Varma]: And she suddenly became very cool for the Hoi Poloi to said they've read her when she

01:33:10.720 --> 01:33:12.080
[Amit Varma]: won the Nobel Prize and all that.

01:33:12.080 --> 01:33:15.120
[Amit Varma]: But like just such an amazing.

01:33:15.120 --> 01:33:17.600
[Guest]: I think she can never write a bad sentence.

01:33:17.600 --> 01:33:18.480
[Guest]: It's not possible.

01:33:18.480 --> 01:33:19.360
[Guest]: Just not possible.

01:33:19.360 --> 01:33:23.200
[Guest]: Like anything, anything that we've read of hers.

01:33:23.200 --> 01:33:25.280
[Guest]: I think she's just brilliant.

01:33:25.280 --> 01:33:29.120
[Amit Varma]: And what strikes me about Alice Munro is that she does with the short story.

01:33:29.120 --> 01:33:35.600
[Amit Varma]: I haven't seen anyone else do to this extent in the sense that in a very short space, she

01:33:35.600 --> 01:33:39.760
[Amit Varma]: will compress such a deep, lovely novelistic world almost.

01:33:39.760 --> 01:33:43.840
[Amit Varma]: It's like she doesn't need to write novels because she can say it all in a short story.

01:33:43.840 --> 01:33:48.240
[Amit Varma]: And the one, my favorite short story of hers is called The Bear Came Over The Mountain.

01:33:48.240 --> 01:33:49.840
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, about amnesia.

01:33:49.840 --> 01:33:50.160
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:33:50.160 --> 01:33:51.120
[Amit Varma]: About this old man.

01:33:51.120 --> 01:33:52.080
[Amit Varma]: Alzheimer's rather.

01:33:52.080 --> 01:33:52.800
[Amit Varma]: Alzheimer's, yeah.

01:33:52.800 --> 01:33:53.600
[Unknown]: And amnesia.

01:33:53.600 --> 01:33:54.800
[Unknown]: Yeah, I don't know about Alzheimer's.

01:33:54.800 --> 01:33:55.600
[Unknown]: You're correct.

01:33:55.600 --> 01:33:59.440
[Guest]: I, but what a beautiful, beautiful story.

01:33:59.440 --> 01:34:02.400
[Guest]: You know, talking about that, the movie is also really very good.

01:34:02.400 --> 01:34:03.280
[Guest]: Okay.

01:34:03.280 --> 01:34:04.240
[Amit Varma]: Based on the short story.

01:34:04.240 --> 01:34:06.480
[Amit Varma]: I saw the movie far from her or something like that.

01:34:07.600 --> 01:34:08.800
[Guest]: Away from her, far from her.

01:34:08.800 --> 01:34:09.440
[Guest]: Away from her.

01:34:09.440 --> 01:34:13.760
[Guest]: Yeah, but I kind of found it, perhaps compared to the story, because I'm just such a fan.

01:34:13.760 --> 01:34:14.240
[Guest]: Yes, yes.

01:34:15.600 --> 01:34:17.360
[Amit Varma]: We will link the story from the show notes.

01:34:17.360 --> 01:34:19.280
[Guest]: Kindly read her.

01:34:19.280 --> 01:34:20.240
[Guest]: Yeah, you must.

01:34:20.240 --> 01:34:23.760
[Guest]: I mean, Monroe is someone who's so close to my heart.

01:34:23.760 --> 01:34:24.160
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:34:24.160 --> 01:34:29.600
[Guest]: Because again, I think, I think when, when authors and books come to you at a time when

01:34:29.600 --> 01:34:35.520
[Guest]: you need them the most, I think they just change the way you are as a person.

01:34:35.520 --> 01:34:36.880
[Guest]: Was that the case with Monroe?

01:34:36.880 --> 01:34:37.920
[Guest]: Yeah, completely.

01:34:37.920 --> 01:34:40.800
[Guest]: She just landed in my lap just like that.

01:34:40.800 --> 01:34:43.840
[Guest]: Like literally, I just went to Lotus bookstore.

01:34:43.840 --> 01:34:45.680
[Guest]: And I love Joyce Carol Oates.

01:34:46.400 --> 01:34:50.080
[Guest]: And, and I was like, okay, time to read something different.

01:34:50.800 --> 01:34:55.120
[Guest]: And I just chanced upon this book called Hateship, Friendship, Loveship.

01:34:55.120 --> 01:34:55.920
[Guest]: Courtship Marriage.

01:34:55.920 --> 01:34:56.720
[Guest]: Courtship Marriage.

01:34:56.720 --> 01:34:59.200
[Guest]: And I was like, okay, let's just pick this up.

01:34:59.200 --> 01:35:02.080
[Guest]: And I never looked back since then.

01:35:02.080 --> 01:35:03.520
[Guest]: I just have to read her.

01:35:04.320 --> 01:35:09.920
[Guest]: And, and even though you've read her, you want to go back to her and read her again.

01:35:09.920 --> 01:35:14.640
[Amit Varma]: And, and often just from the point of view as a writer, like I have gone to her stories

01:35:14.640 --> 01:35:18.080
[Amit Varma]: trying to figure out the craft, like how the hell does she do this?

01:35:18.080 --> 01:35:23.120
[Amit Varma]: To keep a story moving so fluidly and yet pack in so much and pack in a whole universe

01:35:23.120 --> 01:35:23.520
[Guest]: into a story.

01:35:23.520 --> 01:35:26.160
[Guest]: And so many emotions, she'll wring them all out of you.

01:35:26.160 --> 01:35:26.640
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:35:26.640 --> 01:35:31.360
[Guest]: Like when she writes a sentence, it's a central just keep playing in your head over and over

01:35:31.360 --> 01:35:32.080
[Guest]: again.

01:35:32.080 --> 01:35:33.440
[Guest]: It just won't let go.

01:35:33.440 --> 01:35:34.080
[Amit Varma]: Just lovely.

01:35:34.080 --> 01:35:37.600
[Amit Varma]: And if some of you are aspiring writers, it might be interesting to note that her writing

01:35:37.600 --> 01:35:38.960
[Amit Varma]: really happened very late.

01:35:38.960 --> 01:35:41.840
[Unknown]: She really blossomed in her 50s and 60s.

01:35:41.840 --> 01:35:44.480
[Amit Varma]: And her best work is like now in her old age.

01:35:44.480 --> 01:35:49.120
[Amit Varma]: I think in the last 20 years, she's just kind of been knocking it out of the park one story

01:35:49.120 --> 01:35:50.000
[Guest]: at a time.

01:35:50.000 --> 01:35:54.560
[Guest]: There's this other writer who I absolutely adore, this Australian writer called Christina

01:35:54.560 --> 01:35:55.200
[Guest]: Stead.

01:35:55.200 --> 01:35:56.000
[Guest]: Okay, I've never read her.

01:35:56.000 --> 01:35:56.240
[Unknown]: Yeah.

01:35:56.240 --> 01:36:00.880
[Guest]: There's this book called The Man Who Loved Children about how a father, you know, treats

01:36:00.880 --> 01:36:02.560
[Guest]: his children really badly.

01:36:02.560 --> 01:36:06.880
[Guest]: And not, not abuse in the sense, but about their family unit.

01:36:06.880 --> 01:36:08.480
[Guest]: And it's so dysfunctional.

01:36:08.480 --> 01:36:09.680
[Guest]: It's a brilliant book.

01:36:10.480 --> 01:36:12.160
[Guest]: Franzen recommends it a lot.

01:36:12.160 --> 01:36:12.960
[Guest]: Ah, okay.

01:36:12.960 --> 01:36:14.240
[Guest]: And that's how I got to know of it.

01:36:14.240 --> 01:36:21.600
[Guest]: And that's when I read it, way back in 2009, when I think Freedom came out, 2009, 2010.

01:36:21.600 --> 01:36:24.240
[Guest]: And Oprah selected Freedom for her book club.

01:36:24.240 --> 01:36:25.680
[Guest]: And then I read Freedom.

01:36:25.680 --> 01:36:27.280
[Guest]: And I already read Corrections.

01:36:27.280 --> 01:36:28.400
[Guest]: But I love Freedom more.

01:36:28.400 --> 01:36:30.640
[Guest]: And then he spoke about Christina Stead.

01:36:30.640 --> 01:36:31.920
[Guest]: And that's how I got to know of her.

01:36:32.880 --> 01:36:33.600
[Amit Varma]: That's interesting.

01:36:33.600 --> 01:36:39.120
[Amit Varma]: And it kind of brings on a lament about how my reading habit fell a little bit through

01:36:39.120 --> 01:36:39.920
[Amit Varma]: many of those years.

01:36:39.920 --> 01:36:42.320
[Amit Varma]: Like I read Corrections and absolutely loved it.

01:36:42.320 --> 01:36:42.560
[Unknown]: Yeah.

01:36:42.560 --> 01:36:43.680
[Amit Varma]: And I haven't read Freedom.

01:36:43.680 --> 01:36:44.880
[Amit Varma]: You must read Freedom.

01:36:44.880 --> 01:36:45.360
[Guest]: You'll love it.

01:36:45.360 --> 01:36:47.360
[Guest]: And it's a rock and roll.

01:36:47.360 --> 01:36:48.000
[Guest]: Yeah, okay.

01:36:48.000 --> 01:36:49.600
[Guest]: And it's got, it's got music.

01:36:49.600 --> 01:36:51.520
[Guest]: And of course, he loves birds.

01:36:51.520 --> 01:36:52.960
[Guest]: So there's a lot of bird watching.

01:36:53.600 --> 01:36:55.680
[Guest]: And it's again about a dysfunctional family.

01:36:56.560 --> 01:37:00.880
[Guest]: And I don't think anybody else that dysfunctional family better than Franzen does it.

01:37:00.880 --> 01:37:04.160
[Amit Varma]: So the great American writers are very good at dysfunctional family.

01:37:04.160 --> 01:37:05.680
[Guest]: Updike is all dysfunctional.

01:37:06.800 --> 01:37:10.400
[Guest]: Yates also, which he had a very short span.

01:37:11.120 --> 01:37:18.720
[Unknown]: Achiever does a brilliant job in short stories, again, does a brilliant job of the dysfunctionality.

01:37:18.720 --> 01:37:21.120
[Guest]: Ford also does a very good job.

01:37:21.680 --> 01:37:23.440
[Amit Varma]: It's right up the American.

01:37:23.440 --> 01:37:24.400
[Guest]: Yeah, completely.

01:37:25.360 --> 01:37:29.120
[Guest]: I think even the Indian scene, a lot of Bengali writers do that really well.

01:37:29.120 --> 01:37:33.760
[Guest]: I know Asha Poornadevi, who I love, as a short story writer, I was just thinking about her

01:37:33.760 --> 01:37:38.160
[Guest]: when you mentioned Monroe, because she is brilliant.

01:37:38.160 --> 01:37:39.760
[Guest]: I wish more of her works.

01:37:39.760 --> 01:37:40.880
[Guest]: I've never read her.

01:37:40.880 --> 01:37:46.320
[Guest]: Yeah, you know, she was the one who wrote her novels and stories without stepping foot

01:37:46.320 --> 01:37:47.040
[Guest]: out of home.

01:37:47.040 --> 01:37:47.600
[Guest]: Wow.

01:37:47.600 --> 01:37:48.160
[Guest]: Okay.

01:37:48.160 --> 01:37:50.640
[Guest]: And she was this Bengali lady, very unassuming.

01:37:51.520 --> 01:37:57.680
[Guest]: And she wrote about close to 3000 short stories, and about 152 novels.

01:37:57.680 --> 01:37:58.880
[Amit Varma]: 152 novels.

01:37:58.880 --> 01:38:00.320
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, all in Bengali.

01:38:01.040 --> 01:38:02.880
[Guest]: And some of it has been translated, very few.

01:38:03.680 --> 01:38:09.200
[Guest]: But I keep telling Arunabha on Twitter, Arunabha Sinha, that, you know, please translate more

01:38:09.200 --> 01:38:11.440
[Guest]: of her because we need to read more of her.

01:38:11.440 --> 01:38:13.040
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and he's an outstanding translator.

01:38:13.040 --> 01:38:15.920
[Guest]: And he also translates very prolifically, three, four books.

01:38:15.920 --> 01:38:17.040
[Guest]: Oh, yeah, a year, I think.

01:38:18.160 --> 01:38:20.640
[Guest]: But what a book, you must read Asha Poornadevi.

01:38:20.640 --> 01:38:21.440
[Amit Varma]: She's so good.

01:38:21.440 --> 01:38:25.200
[Amit Varma]: In fact, speaking of book to film, another one which struck my mind when you said Bengali

01:38:25.200 --> 01:38:26.240
[Amit Varma]: was Days and Nights.

01:38:26.240 --> 01:38:27.680
[Guest]: Yes, yes.

01:38:29.040 --> 01:38:31.200
[Guest]: I just finished rereading it last night.

01:38:33.040 --> 01:38:38.720
[Guest]: And Robi and all these characters are still so fresh in my mind, as we speak now.

01:38:38.720 --> 01:38:40.240
[Guest]: I love the movie.

01:38:40.240 --> 01:38:41.120
[Guest]: Love the movie.

01:38:41.120 --> 01:38:42.080
[Amit Varma]: Absolutely love the movie.

01:38:42.080 --> 01:38:46.080
[Amit Varma]: And I guess if you want any filmmaker to make a film of your book and therefore to be part

01:38:46.080 --> 01:38:47.840
[Guest]: of this list, it's obviously Shottu Jitra.

01:38:47.840 --> 01:38:49.600
[Guest]: Yeah, of course, of course.

01:38:49.600 --> 01:38:50.240
[Guest]: Hands down.

01:38:50.880 --> 01:38:53.040
[Guest]: Like, I can't think of anyone else.

01:38:53.040 --> 01:38:58.240
[Guest]: And I loved how Choker Bali was done by Ritu Panna Ghosh as well.

01:38:58.240 --> 01:38:59.200
[Guest]: Oh, I haven't seen it.

01:38:59.200 --> 01:39:04.720
[Guest]: Yeah, I love the treatment of the film and how he got the essence of the book pat on.

01:39:05.840 --> 01:39:12.720
[Guest]: So I think, yeah, another movie I would love to be read as a book is Doshar, again by him.

01:39:12.720 --> 01:39:13.760
[Guest]: I don't know if you watched it.

01:39:13.760 --> 01:39:14.560
[Guest]: No.

01:39:14.560 --> 01:39:17.920
[Guest]: Konkona, Sen Sharma and Prasanjit is there.

01:39:17.920 --> 01:39:19.840
[Amit Varma]: Brilliant, brilliant movie.

01:39:20.400 --> 01:39:20.880
[Amit Varma]: So yeah.

01:39:21.520 --> 01:39:22.960
[Amit Varma]: That's something to look out for.

01:39:22.960 --> 01:39:24.080
[Amit Varma]: Let's have your next poem.

01:39:24.080 --> 01:39:24.580
[Guest]: Okay.

01:39:25.360 --> 01:39:28.320
[Guest]: Since we're talking about Sputnik, should I give you a quote from that?

01:39:28.320 --> 01:39:29.120
[Guest]: Sure, please.

01:39:29.120 --> 01:39:29.620
[Guest]: All right.

01:39:30.960 --> 01:39:36.480
[Guest]: And it came to me then that we were wonderful traveling companions, but in the end, no more

01:39:36.480 --> 01:39:40.320
[Guest]: than lonely lumps of metal in their own separate orbits.

01:39:41.280 --> 01:39:44.000
[Guest]: From far off, they look like beautiful shooting stars.

01:39:44.640 --> 01:39:49.680
[Guest]: But in reality, they are nothing more than prisons, where each of us is locked up alone,

01:39:50.400 --> 01:39:51.200
[Guest]: going nowhere.

01:39:51.200 --> 01:39:56.800
[Guest]: When the orbits of these two satellites of ours happened to cross paths, we could be

01:39:56.800 --> 01:40:00.000
[Guest]: together, maybe even open our hearts to each other.

01:40:00.800 --> 01:40:02.720
[Guest]: But that was only for the briefest moment.

01:40:03.600 --> 01:40:09.840
[Guest]: In the next instant, we'd be in absolute solitude, until we burned up and became nothing.

01:40:10.640 --> 01:40:11.440
[Guest]: Lovely.

01:40:11.440 --> 01:40:13.520
[Guest]: I think he just hits a spot.

01:40:15.360 --> 01:40:17.520
[Guest]: And I don't expect him to in any of his books.

01:40:17.520 --> 01:40:21.840
[Guest]: In any of his books, he just, they just come out of the pages and grabs you.

01:40:21.840 --> 01:40:22.400
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:40:22.400 --> 01:40:25.600
[Amit Varma]: And you're like, okay, I have to pay attention to what he's writing.

01:40:25.600 --> 01:40:27.600
[Amit Varma]: Which books do you wish were made into movies?

01:40:28.640 --> 01:40:29.920
[Guest]: No, those I don't wish.

01:40:30.560 --> 01:40:31.680
[Guest]: Like, I'm very skeptical.

01:40:31.680 --> 01:40:33.360
[Guest]: I love 100 Years of Solitude.

01:40:33.360 --> 01:40:35.280
[Guest]: For example, it was very hard to make something.

01:40:35.280 --> 01:40:36.480
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, but they are, right?

01:40:36.480 --> 01:40:37.040
[Amit Varma]: They've tried.

01:40:37.040 --> 01:40:38.640
[Guest]: Yeah, making a series.

01:40:39.440 --> 01:40:44.960
[Guest]: I just hope somebody has understood the book to be able to make it into a series.

01:40:44.960 --> 01:40:49.360
[Guest]: And a suitable boy, which I never wanted them to make into a series, but they are.

01:40:50.240 --> 01:40:51.680
[Guest]: So that's something that I don't want.

01:40:52.560 --> 01:40:54.320
[Guest]: I wish they would leave some books alone.

01:40:55.520 --> 01:40:58.080
[Amit Varma]: Well, you're not forced to watch it.

01:40:58.080 --> 01:41:00.960
[Amit Varma]: And you never know, sometimes they can surprise you in a good way, like with The Dead.

01:41:00.960 --> 01:41:02.960
[Amit Varma]: I mean, who would have thought it to make the kind of film?

01:41:02.960 --> 01:41:03.760
[Guest]: Yeah, that's true.

01:41:04.400 --> 01:41:09.280
[Guest]: But like, you know, Bel Canto, they made by Ann Patchett, starring Julianne Moore.

01:41:09.280 --> 01:41:12.480
[Guest]: And I haven't watched the movie because I'm scared.

01:41:12.480 --> 01:41:14.960
[Guest]: I love the book way too much.

01:41:15.840 --> 01:41:17.760
[Amit Varma]: The fear of the cinema hall.

01:41:17.760 --> 01:41:20.800
[Guest]: Yeah, like I watched Midnight's Children.

01:41:21.360 --> 01:41:22.960
[Guest]: I wanted to puke into a bucket.

01:41:23.760 --> 01:41:25.680
[Guest]: It disappointed me so much.

01:41:26.480 --> 01:41:30.960
[Guest]: And no, I'm not saying that for the director or the way it is, but it's a big book.

01:41:31.920 --> 01:41:36.320
[Guest]: You cannot compress it into two and a half hours of movie.

01:41:37.040 --> 01:41:41.760
[Guest]: You have to tell it the way the author meant it to be written.

01:41:41.760 --> 01:41:43.360
[Amit Varma]: And to be interpreted.

01:41:43.360 --> 01:41:47.520
[Amit Varma]: If you think about it, even with the English patient, the film made that cinematic choice

01:41:47.520 --> 01:41:51.600
[Amit Varma]: of focusing on sort of one particular strand of the book, like the Indian characters, for

01:41:51.600 --> 01:41:52.960
[Guest]: example, very major in the book.

01:41:52.960 --> 01:41:55.360
[Guest]: But yes, but not there in the movie.

01:41:55.360 --> 01:41:58.560
[Guest]: You know, one book to movie, which I absolutely love is The Namesake.

01:41:59.440 --> 01:42:08.560
[Guest]: I absolutely love Jhumpa Lahiri's adaptation, as in Miranayar's adaptation of Jhumpa Lahiri's

01:42:08.560 --> 01:42:11.440
[Guest]: book, which is stunning.

01:42:11.440 --> 01:42:15.280
[Guest]: I mean, Tabu and Irrfan Khan and everybody's acted so well.

01:42:16.320 --> 01:42:18.240
[Amit Varma]: So, yeah, that's again one of my favorites.

01:42:18.240 --> 01:42:19.360
[Amit Varma]: Great writer, great director.

01:42:19.360 --> 01:42:21.520
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, a writer I discovered.

01:42:21.520 --> 01:42:27.120
[Amit Varma]: So Jhumpa Lahiri was on this podcast called Conversations with Tyler, with Tyler Cowen.

01:42:27.120 --> 01:42:31.360
[Amit Varma]: And in that, she mentioned she was going through this phase where she was learning a new language

01:42:31.360 --> 01:42:33.520
[Amit Varma]: and writing in it, in her case, Italian.

01:42:33.520 --> 01:42:36.560
[Amit Varma]: And she spoke about another author called Agatha Kristoff.

01:42:37.840 --> 01:42:40.320
[Amit Varma]: At first, I thought it's a typo of Agatha Christie.

01:42:40.320 --> 01:42:43.600
[Guest]: But for a moment, it seemed that way.

01:42:43.600 --> 01:42:44.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:42:44.000 --> 01:42:48.160
[Amit Varma]: So she spoke about an author called Agatha Kristoff, who basically, I think, moved during

01:42:48.160 --> 01:42:51.680
[Amit Varma]: the war to France, if I'm not mistaken, learned a new language and then wrote books in that

01:42:51.680 --> 01:42:52.880
[Amit Varma]: language from scratch.

01:42:52.880 --> 01:42:55.760
[Amit Varma]: In her new language, which she learned in her adult life.

01:42:55.760 --> 01:43:01.600
[Amit Varma]: It's a trilogy, I forget what it's called, but it's magnificent, very sort of bare, sparse,

01:43:01.600 --> 01:43:02.560
[Unknown]: minimal language.

01:43:04.320 --> 01:43:05.040
[Guest]: You've read it?

01:43:05.040 --> 01:43:05.520
[Guest]: I've read it.

01:43:05.520 --> 01:43:06.080
[Guest]: Yeah, obviously.

01:43:06.080 --> 01:43:07.920
[Guest]: I think the Notebook is the first book.

01:43:07.920 --> 01:43:08.880
[Guest]: The Notebook is the first one.

01:43:08.880 --> 01:43:10.240
[Guest]: Yes, I remember this one now.

01:43:10.240 --> 01:43:11.520
[Guest]: Yes, it just struck me.

01:43:11.520 --> 01:43:12.160
[Guest]: Yes.

01:43:12.160 --> 01:43:12.640
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:43:12.640 --> 01:43:13.600
[Guest]: Agatha Kristoff.

01:43:13.600 --> 01:43:14.080
[Guest]: Yes.

01:43:14.080 --> 01:43:15.200
[Guest]: It's a lovely trilogy.

01:43:15.200 --> 01:43:17.280
[Amit Varma]: And I recommend everyone.

01:43:17.280 --> 01:43:20.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I have the omnibus copy with all three books.

01:43:20.000 --> 01:43:23.840
[Guest]: I think Strand used to sell this one a lot.

01:43:23.840 --> 01:43:24.480
[Guest]: Oh, really?

01:43:24.480 --> 01:43:25.440
[Guest]: Strand Fort, man.

01:43:25.440 --> 01:43:26.880
[Amit Varma]: Oh, I got mine from Amazon.

01:43:26.880 --> 01:43:28.160
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, they used to sell a lot.

01:43:28.800 --> 01:43:31.520
[Amit Varma]: And Mr. Shanbhag knew what he was doing after all.

01:43:31.520 --> 01:43:32.640
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, this is...

01:43:32.640 --> 01:43:34.240
[Guest]: He knew it right down to the pad.

01:43:34.240 --> 01:43:40.160
[Amit Varma]: It's a lovely... and speaking of a bare, sparse language, do you sort of have specific literary

01:43:40.160 --> 01:43:42.560
[Amit Varma]: tastes which stop you from enjoying certain writers?

01:43:42.560 --> 01:43:50.000
[Amit Varma]: For example, in my case, I simply don't like the sort of flamboyant, over-stylized kind

01:43:50.000 --> 01:43:53.040
[Amit Varma]: of writing that say Rushdie and Arundhati Roy do.

01:43:53.040 --> 01:43:57.600
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, so I'm much more a kind of person who'll read Vikram Seth or Amitav Ghosh or,

01:43:57.600 --> 01:44:00.480
[Amit Varma]: you know, and all the Japanese writers, because it might be some

01:44:00.480 --> 01:44:06.000
[Amit Varma]: intrinsic quality in their language, which lends itself to simplicity and minimalism.

01:44:06.000 --> 01:44:11.200
[Amit Varma]: But the more flamboyant a writer gets, the harder, even if I can appreciate some of the

01:44:11.200 --> 01:44:15.200
[Amit Varma]: flamboyance, and interestingly, Rushdie's flamboyance is only there in his fiction.

01:44:15.200 --> 01:44:16.800
[Amit Varma]: I find his nonfiction much more readable.

01:44:16.800 --> 01:44:19.840
[Guest]: Yeah, his nonfiction, in fact, is very interesting.

01:44:19.840 --> 01:44:22.960
[Guest]: But I think for me, nothing of that sort, really.

01:44:22.960 --> 01:44:30.640
[Guest]: Not really. But I think some writers I just don't veer towards, like I'll never,

01:44:30.640 --> 01:44:32.240
[Guest]: thrillers, I can't stand them.

01:44:32.880 --> 01:44:34.400
[Unknown]: I just don't, just the way it's written.

01:44:35.200 --> 01:44:39.280
[Guest]: Just, and not about, I have to wait till the end to figure things out.

01:44:39.280 --> 01:44:42.960
[Guest]: But I just can't read a thriller, no matter how hard I try.

01:44:43.920 --> 01:44:46.320
[Guest]: Or horror, for the longest time I couldn't.

01:44:47.440 --> 01:44:51.040
[Guest]: But King makes it palpable, so I'll read it.

01:44:51.040 --> 01:44:53.200
[Guest]: But otherwise, I won't read horror at all.

01:44:53.200 --> 01:44:54.720
[Amit Varma]: Oh, do you read any science fiction?

01:44:55.280 --> 01:44:58.320
[Guest]: Um, yeah, I mean, no, not really.

01:44:58.320 --> 01:45:00.640
[Guest]: Science fiction cloaked as fantasy, yeah, sure.

01:45:01.200 --> 01:45:02.640
[Guest]: I'll read, I love that.

01:45:02.640 --> 01:45:05.760
[Guest]: But not science fiction, like I can't read Asimov.

01:45:05.760 --> 01:45:06.400
[Unknown]: Yeah.

01:45:06.960 --> 01:45:08.160
[Unknown]: Just cannot.

01:45:08.160 --> 01:45:09.760
[Guest]: But I love Philip K. Dick.

01:45:10.400 --> 01:45:11.360
[Guest]: I don't know why.

01:45:12.320 --> 01:45:14.240
[Guest]: But, but yeah, I can't answer that.

01:45:14.240 --> 01:45:16.080
[Guest]: But I love Philip K. Dick.

01:45:16.080 --> 01:45:20.080
[Amit Varma]: If you read someone, like some of the newer guys aren't even, I mean, it's hard to even

01:45:20.080 --> 01:45:23.760
[Amit Varma]: call them science fiction because they're not like how you imagine cliched, hard science

01:45:23.760 --> 01:45:24.800
[Guest]: fiction to be.

01:45:24.800 --> 01:45:26.320
[Guest]: People like Ken Liu, have you read him?

01:45:26.320 --> 01:45:27.600
[Guest]: Yeah, Ken Liu, I like a lot.

01:45:27.600 --> 01:45:28.400
[Amit Varma]: Paper Menagerie.

01:45:28.400 --> 01:45:30.000
[Guest]: I love that collection of short stories.

01:45:30.000 --> 01:45:30.800
[Guest]: Lovely collection.

01:45:30.800 --> 01:45:31.360
[Guest]: Love that.

01:45:31.360 --> 01:45:33.680
[Guest]: Or that three-body problem writer.

01:45:33.680 --> 01:45:35.520
[Amit Varma]: Sissin Liu, I don't know how to pronounce it.

01:45:35.520 --> 01:45:36.240
[Amit Varma]: Sissin Liu.

01:45:36.240 --> 01:45:38.880
[Amit Varma]: I've read two books, I have to read the third one.

01:45:38.880 --> 01:45:42.000
[Guest]: Or N.K. Jemisin, who I absolutely adore.

01:45:42.000 --> 01:45:42.960
[Guest]: Ted Chiang.

01:45:42.960 --> 01:45:44.240
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, Ted Chiang, N.K. Jemisin.

01:45:44.240 --> 01:45:45.600
[Amit Varma]: On whom Short Story Arrival was made.

01:45:45.600 --> 01:45:46.400
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, yeah.

01:45:46.400 --> 01:45:49.120
[Guest]: He's come up with a new collection, Exhalation.

01:45:49.120 --> 01:45:52.400
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, which I've got, but I haven't started.

01:45:52.400 --> 01:45:54.000
[Amit Varma]: Neither have I, I have to read it yet.

01:45:54.000 --> 01:45:57.440
[Amit Varma]: Actually, wait, I've read, I think the title story from it, which is very interesting.

01:45:58.400 --> 01:46:02.080
[Amit Varma]: And the good thing about a lot of these so-called science fiction writers and even a lot of the

01:46:02.080 --> 01:46:08.240
[Amit Varma]: so-called science fiction films that come is that this quote unquote genre is going

01:46:08.240 --> 01:46:14.160
[Amit Varma]: to places which other literature doesn't seem to be rushing into so eagerly and asking these

01:46:14.160 --> 01:46:15.840
[Amit Varma]: big existential questions.

01:46:15.840 --> 01:46:20.480
[Amit Varma]: You know, like even with, say, a film like Blade Runner, you know, the new Blade Runner.

01:46:20.480 --> 01:46:22.000
[Guest]: Even Minority Report for that matter.

01:46:22.000 --> 01:46:25.760
[Amit Varma]: Even Minority Report or, you know, there's a film called Durs Machina.

01:46:25.760 --> 01:46:27.680
[Guest]: Yeah, I've heard of it, but I haven't watched it.

01:46:27.680 --> 01:46:30.320
[Amit Varma]: It's made by Alex Garland.

01:46:30.320 --> 01:46:31.920
[Amit Varma]: The guy who wrote The Beach.

01:46:31.920 --> 01:46:34.560
[Amit Varma]: The guy who wrote The Beach and Tesseract, which I like more than The Beach.

01:46:34.560 --> 01:46:38.240
[Guest]: Yes, Tesseract is a better novel than The Beach, yes, I agree, completely.

01:46:38.240 --> 01:46:39.280
[Amit Varma]: So it's a very interesting film.

01:46:39.280 --> 01:46:45.520
[Amit Varma]: So like Durs Machina will, for example, go into areas like, you know, how the moral values

01:46:45.520 --> 01:46:49.360
[Amit Varma]: you attach to AI, should you kill an artificial being and so on.

01:46:49.360 --> 01:46:54.720
[Amit Varma]: You know, Blade Runner looked at things like how identity is constructed or the fallibility

01:46:54.720 --> 01:46:55.600
[Amit Varma]: of memory.

01:46:55.600 --> 01:47:00.560
[Amit Varma]: And all of these really big questions are questions that I think science fiction is

01:47:00.560 --> 01:47:05.760
[Amit Varma]: ideally placed to answer because it can take those sort of that one further step that you

01:47:05.760 --> 01:47:06.320
[Guest]: need to take.

01:47:06.320 --> 01:47:12.400
[Guest]: Like Ursula K. Le Guin, The Left Hand of Darkness, about gender and about identity and politics

01:47:12.400 --> 01:47:13.200
[Guest]: of gender.

01:47:13.200 --> 01:47:17.600
[Amit Varma]: So I'm sometimes like, I'm not a hard science fiction reader in that sense.

01:47:18.400 --> 01:47:20.800
[Amit Varma]: I'm probably very ignorant about most of science fiction.

01:47:20.800 --> 01:47:26.560
[Amit Varma]: But I do find that it's really unfair to sort of knock something as, oh, this is a genre,

01:47:26.560 --> 01:47:29.600
[Unknown]: like this is sci-fi, or this is crime mystery, or this is whatever.

01:47:30.160 --> 01:47:33.920
[Amit Varma]: When you are asking the big questions and you're doing everything literature should

01:47:33.920 --> 01:47:34.160
[Guest]: do.

01:47:34.160 --> 01:47:35.600
[Guest]: That I think makes sense.

01:47:36.320 --> 01:47:40.240
[Guest]: But other than that, I don't think I can read a thriller at least.

01:47:40.240 --> 01:47:47.280
[Guest]: I read it when I had to read Puzo and Sydney Sheldon, which I love.

01:47:48.240 --> 01:47:50.640
[Guest]: And for the longest time, I thought it was a woman.

01:47:51.520 --> 01:47:52.560
[Amit Varma]: Then I figured no.

01:47:52.560 --> 01:47:55.520
[Amit Varma]: Did your uncle pass on his love of Alastair Maclean to you?

01:47:55.520 --> 01:47:58.720
[Guest]: No, I just cannot.

01:47:58.720 --> 01:48:01.360
[Guest]: All those guns and weapons and wars, I just cannot.

01:48:02.160 --> 01:48:03.680
[Amit Varma]: I find it extremely boring.

01:48:04.480 --> 01:48:07.760
[Amit Varma]: Right now, I'll read out a poem now because we have to get to your next poem.

01:48:07.760 --> 01:48:09.120
[Amit Varma]: Before that, we'll have to.

01:48:09.120 --> 01:48:12.240
[Amit Varma]: Okay, this is by a poet called CP Savafi.

01:48:13.600 --> 01:48:14.080
[Guest]: Oh, yes.

01:48:14.880 --> 01:48:21.280
[Amit Varma]: I mean, of course, this particular poem is translated by Edmund Keeley and is called

01:48:21.280 --> 01:48:22.240
[Amit Varma]: The City.

01:48:22.240 --> 01:48:24.240
[Amit Varma]: And much of the first part is actually a quote.

01:48:24.240 --> 01:48:26.960
[Amit Varma]: So I'll say stop quote at the end of it, as I usually do.

01:48:26.960 --> 01:48:28.800
[Amit Varma]: But that doesn't mean I have stopped.

01:48:28.800 --> 01:48:32.080
[Amit Varma]: It means a poem has moved on from the quote to the normal thing.

01:48:32.960 --> 01:48:34.800
[Amit Varma]: The City by Constantine Cavafy.

01:48:34.800 --> 01:48:40.080
[Amit Varma]: You said, quote, I'll go to another country, go to another shore, find another city better

01:48:40.080 --> 01:48:41.040
[Amit Varma]: than this one.

01:48:41.040 --> 01:48:43.680
[Amit Varma]: Whatever I try to do is fated to turn out wrong.

01:48:43.680 --> 01:48:46.080
[Amit Varma]: And my heart lies buried like something dead.

01:48:46.640 --> 01:48:49.360
[Amit Varma]: How long can I let my mind moulder in this place?

01:48:49.360 --> 01:48:54.720
[Amit Varma]: Wherever I turn, wherever I look, I see the black ruins of my life here, where I've spent

01:48:54.720 --> 01:48:57.680
[Amit Varma]: so many years, wasted them, destroyed them totally.

01:48:58.240 --> 01:48:59.280
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

01:48:59.280 --> 01:49:00.240
[Amit Varma]: The poem continues.

01:49:00.960 --> 01:49:03.600
[Amit Varma]: You won't find a new country, won't find another shore.

01:49:03.600 --> 01:49:04.800
[Amit Varma]: Won't find another shore.

01:49:04.800 --> 01:49:06.720
[Amit Varma]: The city will always pursue you.

01:49:06.720 --> 01:49:11.680
[Amit Varma]: You'll walk the same streets, grow old in the same neighborhoods, turn gray in the same

01:49:11.680 --> 01:49:12.400
[Amit Varma]: houses.

01:49:12.400 --> 01:49:14.560
[Amit Varma]: You'll always end up in the city.

01:49:14.560 --> 01:49:16.320
[Amit Varma]: Don't hope for things elsewhere.

01:49:16.320 --> 01:49:17.440
[Amit Varma]: There's no ship for you.

01:49:17.440 --> 01:49:18.560
[Amit Varma]: There's no road.

01:49:18.560 --> 01:49:22.960
[Amit Varma]: Now that you wasted your life here, in this small corner, you've destroyed it everywhere

01:49:22.960 --> 01:49:23.520
[Amit Varma]: in the world.

01:49:24.080 --> 01:49:24.580
[Guest]: Wow.

01:49:25.440 --> 01:49:26.560
[Guest]: It's just something else.

01:49:26.560 --> 01:49:27.280
[Guest]: Spectacular.

01:49:27.920 --> 01:49:28.400
[Guest]: Indeed.

01:49:28.400 --> 01:49:29.760
[Guest]: Spectacular indeed.

01:49:29.760 --> 01:49:35.760
[Guest]: Reminds me of Ishiguro, for some strange reason, this poem took me to Ishiguro immediately

01:49:35.760 --> 01:49:36.720
[Guest]: and never let me go.

01:49:36.720 --> 01:49:37.360
[Guest]: I don't know why.

01:49:38.160 --> 01:49:38.960
[Guest]: It just happened.

01:49:39.760 --> 01:49:43.440
[Guest]: I think something's just, and we have to go and reread.

01:49:43.440 --> 01:49:46.320
[Amit Varma]: And it's interesting, you were mentioning how you would go to British Council every

01:49:46.320 --> 01:49:47.120
[Amit Varma]: weekend.

01:49:47.120 --> 01:49:53.440
[Amit Varma]: I discovered Ishiguro in these summers in the early 90s, when I was in the hostel in

01:49:53.440 --> 01:49:57.600
[Amit Varma]: Ferguson College, Pune, and I'd walk over for the air conditioning to the British Council

01:49:57.600 --> 01:49:58.960
[Unknown]: library nearby.

01:49:58.960 --> 01:50:03.360
[Guest]: And so I read his early books, The Remains of the Day, A Pale View of Hills.

01:50:03.360 --> 01:50:06.240
[Guest]: I discovered Actwood also in the British Library.

01:50:06.240 --> 01:50:06.720
[Guest]: Oh, okay.

01:50:06.720 --> 01:50:07.520
[Guest]: There you go.

01:50:07.520 --> 01:50:09.360
[Guest]: So there you go.

01:50:09.360 --> 01:50:09.840
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:50:09.840 --> 01:50:11.120
[Guest]: Otherwise, I didn't know of her.

01:50:12.720 --> 01:50:14.160
[Guest]: So very interesting.

01:50:14.160 --> 01:50:16.560
[Guest]: I mean, you don't know of anyone till you know of them.

01:50:16.560 --> 01:50:19.040
[Guest]: Till you know of them, that's true.

01:50:19.040 --> 01:50:21.600
[Guest]: I just, you know, there's this other quote, I'm sorry, I'm quoting.

01:50:21.600 --> 01:50:30.080
[Guest]: It's called Mother of Pearl by Melinda Haynes, which is about a black man falling in love

01:50:30.720 --> 01:50:37.600
[Guest]: or taking care of a 16, 17 year old white trash girl, so to say, as it happens in the

01:50:37.600 --> 01:50:41.120
[Guest]: book, and how the delicate tender relationship they share.

01:50:41.840 --> 01:50:45.360
[Guest]: So there's a quote from the book that just stands out completely.

01:50:45.360 --> 01:50:48.320
[Guest]: And I love it because it's so relevant to the book that I've written.

01:50:48.320 --> 01:50:50.880
[Guest]: And so I want to...

01:50:50.880 --> 01:50:51.600
[Guest]: Go ahead, please.

01:50:51.600 --> 01:50:54.160
[Guest]: So going by what you do, start quote.

01:50:54.880 --> 01:50:57.200
[Amit Varma]: Or just quote instead of quote, not start quote.

01:50:57.200 --> 01:51:01.840
[Guest]: Sometimes partial kindness kills a person as bad as partial knowing.

01:51:02.880 --> 01:51:05.040
[Guest]: Judy said this while she hugged the dress.

01:51:06.000 --> 01:51:12.880
[Guest]: But then sometimes partial kindness and partial knowing is the two best things in the world.

01:51:12.880 --> 01:51:13.920
[Guest]: Stop quote.

01:51:13.920 --> 01:51:19.200
[Guest]: So given that my book is about kindness in a way and knowing in a way.

01:51:19.200 --> 01:51:19.840
[Guest]: So yeah.

01:51:19.840 --> 01:51:23.040
[Amit Varma]: How do you feel about your book now that it's kind of out there?

01:51:23.040 --> 01:51:26.560
[Guest]: Like you've been a reader throughout and now this is actually your own book.

01:51:26.560 --> 01:51:30.880
[Guest]: I felt I want to disassociate myself from the book only because I feel I'm not done

01:51:30.880 --> 01:51:32.240
[Guest]: justice in terms of writing.

01:51:32.880 --> 01:51:38.000
[Guest]: And then when people quote to me from my book, or they tweet at me with lines from the book,

01:51:38.000 --> 01:51:39.280
[Guest]: I feel very awkward.

01:51:39.280 --> 01:51:41.120
[Amit Varma]: I am hereby going to make you feel awkward.

01:51:41.120 --> 01:51:45.600
[Amit Varma]: I'm going to interrupt you and I'm going to read out this very nice sentence from page

01:51:45.600 --> 01:51:47.520
[Amit Varma]: three that early the good writing starts.

01:51:48.160 --> 01:51:52.800
[Amit Varma]: Quote, and she was like how the matriarch of a good South Bombay household should be

01:51:52.800 --> 01:51:57.120
[Amit Varma]: honorable and relentless in putting others down, even if it was her own family.

01:51:57.120 --> 01:51:57.760
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

01:51:57.760 --> 01:51:58.880
[Guest]: That's a very nice sentence.

01:51:58.880 --> 01:51:59.680
[Guest]: I like it.

01:51:59.680 --> 01:52:05.200
[Guest]: Kerala matriarch actually came to mind when I was writing, but she was like that.

01:52:06.240 --> 01:52:10.800
[Guest]: From what I've also heard, my grandmother was extremely stern and staunch.

01:52:10.800 --> 01:52:14.560
[Guest]: I think people also to go in a different trajectory.

01:52:14.560 --> 01:52:19.040
[Guest]: When they came from Pakistan to India, I think they became hard in the process.

01:52:19.680 --> 01:52:22.080
[Guest]: They lost their softness, they lost their innocence.

01:52:22.800 --> 01:52:26.960
[Guest]: And she was married off really early to my grandfather as young as she was 11.

01:52:27.760 --> 01:52:36.240
[Guest]: And then when you are young and you experience such pain in leaving home and leaving family,

01:52:36.240 --> 01:52:39.200
[Guest]: I think it just hardens you to a very large extent.

01:52:39.200 --> 01:52:43.520
[Guest]: And then for you to show what you really feel and express yourself so difficult.

01:52:44.160 --> 01:52:49.360
[Guest]: And now I understand this, of course, about a lot of people, which earlier I wouldn't.

01:52:50.480 --> 01:52:55.600
[Guest]: But back to this, I find it very awkward now that the book is out, honestly, because I

01:52:55.600 --> 01:52:56.720
[Guest]: don't know how to deal with it.

01:52:57.680 --> 01:52:58.720
[Guest]: I don't know what to do with it.

01:52:58.720 --> 01:53:05.280
[Guest]: And then I'm like, just like either I soak in what it has to offer or just rejected like

01:53:05.280 --> 01:53:07.280
[Guest]: a stepchild and not look at it ever again.

01:53:07.280 --> 01:53:10.000
[Guest]: But didn't that happen to you when your book came out?

01:53:10.000 --> 01:53:14.800
[Amit Varma]: I think it, as I think I've told you, I wish it had never come out.

01:53:14.800 --> 01:53:17.040
[Guest]: So there you go, it's the same thing.

01:53:17.040 --> 01:53:19.440
[Amit Varma]: No, I mean, I think I let myself down.

01:53:19.440 --> 01:53:26.400
[Guest]: No, so when you read so much, Amit, I also feel that you want to, like, I want one perfect

01:53:26.400 --> 01:53:26.880
[Guest]: sentence.

01:53:26.880 --> 01:53:29.040
[Guest]: I can't find a single perfect sentence in my book.

01:53:29.040 --> 01:53:30.000
[Guest]: I just read one out.

01:53:30.000 --> 01:53:36.160
[Guest]: No, I just want to be like, when you read Munro and then you read Atwood, you read Murakami,

01:53:36.160 --> 01:53:45.600
[Guest]: you read people from other languages, writing so beautifully, like Marquez or Isabel Allende

01:53:45.600 --> 01:53:46.560
[Guest]: and all those people.

01:53:47.200 --> 01:53:49.520
[Guest]: And you're like, wow, what writing.

01:53:49.520 --> 01:53:51.040
[Guest]: Who are the Indian writers you like?

01:53:51.040 --> 01:53:54.240
[Guest]: I love, I absolutely admire Shanta Gokhale.

01:53:54.960 --> 01:53:56.560
[Guest]: I love Shashidesh Pandey.

01:53:57.200 --> 01:53:59.120
[Guest]: I love Ghosh's earlier work.

01:53:59.120 --> 01:54:06.800
[Guest]: I absolutely adore Vikram Seth, Eunice, a big, big, big influence in my life, through

01:54:06.800 --> 01:54:09.600
[Guest]: her writing and through the way she was as a person.

01:54:09.600 --> 01:54:10.400
[Guest]: She taught you?

01:54:10.400 --> 01:54:14.080
[Guest]: Yeah, no, but, but, but, yeah, but great.

01:54:14.080 --> 01:54:19.600
[Guest]: Just, just absolutely brilliant woman, who Indian, who else do I love?

01:54:20.400 --> 01:54:23.040
[Guest]: I love Niranjana Roy's writing.

01:54:23.040 --> 01:54:29.840
[Guest]: When, when I read how she talks about cats and the love that she projects into her books

01:54:29.840 --> 01:54:32.880
[Guest]: about them, it just makes my heart sing.

01:54:32.880 --> 01:54:34.720
[Amit Varma]: I absolutely love her writing.

01:54:34.720 --> 01:54:35.760
[Amit Varma]: Very good friend of mine.

01:54:35.760 --> 01:54:37.440
[Amit Varma]: And she's just finished her new book.

01:54:37.440 --> 01:54:37.760
[Guest]: Yes.

01:54:37.760 --> 01:54:39.040
[Guest]: But it's not about cats.

01:54:39.040 --> 01:54:41.200
[Guest]: I know, but still I can't wait for it.

01:54:41.200 --> 01:54:42.560
[Guest]: It's about crime in Haryana.

01:54:42.560 --> 01:54:43.040
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:54:43.040 --> 01:54:46.000
[Guest]: So I like Annie Zehdi's work.

01:54:46.000 --> 01:54:48.640
[Guest]: I mean, it's like deceptively simple.

01:54:49.280 --> 01:54:50.240
[Amit Varma]: Her new novel's just out?

01:54:50.240 --> 01:54:51.280
[Amit Varma]: Yes, Prelude to Arrive.

01:54:51.280 --> 01:54:51.840
[Amit Varma]: Have you read it?

01:54:51.840 --> 01:54:52.480
[Unknown]: Yeah.

01:54:52.480 --> 01:54:53.840
[Unknown]: I enjoyed it a lot.

01:54:53.840 --> 01:54:54.400
[Unknown]: Yeah.

01:54:54.400 --> 01:54:54.720
[Unknown]: Yeah.

01:54:54.720 --> 01:55:00.640
[Guest]: So I also like Anita Nair, something magical about her writing.

01:55:01.360 --> 01:55:05.040
[Guest]: But, but yeah, I look at it from a distance and I love what she does.

01:55:05.040 --> 01:55:08.880
[Amit Varma]: And given that you're in Bombay, and I presume that you also do the Lit Festival circuit a

01:55:08.880 --> 01:55:13.040
[Amit Varma]: little bit, you must be meeting writers that you've read and then you meet them.

01:55:13.040 --> 01:55:14.400
[Amit Varma]: And how is that experience?

01:55:14.400 --> 01:55:17.760
[Guest]: Is it like, does it change the way you look at it?

01:55:17.760 --> 01:55:26.880
[Guest]: You know, I met Andar Jai in Jaipur, and like a fool, I told him to sign on a page of the

01:55:26.880 --> 01:55:32.320
[Guest]: English patient that I loved so much, that one line, that if I give my heart to you,

01:55:32.320 --> 01:55:33.120
[Guest]: will you break it?

01:55:33.920 --> 01:55:39.680
[Guest]: Or something to that effect, if I give you my heart, I hope you get what I'm saying.

01:55:39.680 --> 01:55:41.200
[Guest]: He refused to do that.

01:55:41.200 --> 01:55:41.840
[Guest]: Why?

01:55:41.840 --> 01:55:44.160
[Guest]: Because he's like, oh, I don't want to sign in the middle of a book.

01:55:44.160 --> 01:55:47.840
[Guest]: And I made him and he gave me the dirty look.

01:55:47.840 --> 01:55:52.160
[Guest]: And then right after he signed, he didn't sign for me, he didn't say for Vivek, he just

01:55:52.160 --> 01:55:55.120
[Guest]: said, whatever, scribbled something, his initials or whatever.

01:55:57.440 --> 01:56:02.720
[Guest]: In a very dramatic moment, I just gave the book to somebody else and I walked out from

01:56:02.720 --> 01:56:04.000
[Guest]: there in front of him.

01:56:04.000 --> 01:56:04.480
[Guest]: Ouch.

01:56:05.600 --> 01:56:07.200
[Guest]: But I didn't expect that from him.

01:56:07.200 --> 01:56:11.440
[Guest]: I love the guy and I still will always love what he writes and I will pick up what he

01:56:11.440 --> 01:56:12.000
[Guest]: writes.

01:56:12.000 --> 01:56:14.320
[Amit Varma]: That's churlish of him.

01:56:14.320 --> 01:56:16.560
[Guest]: Yeah, but I didn't like the way he behaved.

01:56:16.560 --> 01:56:20.480
[Amit Varma]: So I think never meet your heroes, never meet your heroes.

01:56:20.480 --> 01:56:22.560
[Amit Varma]: You've met Alice Munro, you once told me.

01:56:22.560 --> 01:56:24.640
[Guest]: Yes, I have, it was beautiful.

01:56:25.280 --> 01:56:26.640
[Unknown]: It was in Canada.

01:56:26.640 --> 01:56:30.560
[Guest]: I had gone there for something else and I just happened to be in the bookshop where

01:56:30.560 --> 01:56:31.280
[Unknown]: she was reading.

01:56:32.240 --> 01:56:33.840
[Guest]: I'm very rare that she does this.

01:56:34.720 --> 01:56:37.840
[Guest]: But I was just very honored to do that.

01:56:37.840 --> 01:56:43.360
[Guest]: I got my copy signed and she was very gracious about the meeting and it was something else

01:56:43.360 --> 01:56:44.080
[Guest]: altogether.

01:56:45.360 --> 01:56:48.560
[Amit Varma]: You should have given her the English patient and asked her to sign on that line to see

01:56:48.560 --> 01:56:49.520
[Guest]: if she does it.

01:56:50.640 --> 01:56:52.080
[Guest]: Yeah, she even liked the book.

01:56:52.640 --> 01:56:53.520
[Unknown]: I know I loved it.

01:56:54.480 --> 01:56:57.920
[Guest]: I still like Andarje a lot, his writing, but I don't think I want to meet him.

01:56:58.640 --> 01:57:00.880
[Guest]: We all have feet of clay and it's very scary.

01:57:01.440 --> 01:57:02.160
[Unknown]: Yeah.

01:57:02.160 --> 01:57:03.040
[Guest]: So I don't want to.

01:57:03.920 --> 01:57:06.000
[Guest]: Yeah, but I still want to idealize them.

01:57:06.000 --> 01:57:07.360
[Guest]: And that I'll never stop doing.

01:57:08.080 --> 01:57:09.120
[Amit Varma]: Your turn to read a poem.

01:57:09.840 --> 01:57:10.560
[Guest]: Yeah, sorry.

01:57:10.560 --> 01:57:19.840
[Guest]: And last I have with me, it's called Possibilities by this writer called, I don't know how to

01:57:19.840 --> 01:57:24.800
[Guest]: pronounce her name, Vistlava Simborska.

01:57:24.800 --> 01:57:27.200
[Amit Varma]: Yes, I don't know how to pronounce her name either.

01:57:27.200 --> 01:57:28.320
[Amit Varma]: It's called Possibilities.

01:57:29.040 --> 01:57:30.240
[Guest]: I'll be very quick with it.

01:57:31.200 --> 01:57:32.400
[Guest]: I prefer movies.

01:57:32.400 --> 01:57:33.440
[Guest]: I prefer cats.

01:57:33.440 --> 01:57:36.000
[Guest]: I prefer the oaks along the water.

01:57:36.640 --> 01:57:38.560
[Guest]: I prefer Dickens to Dostoevsky.

01:57:39.360 --> 01:57:43.200
[Guest]: I prefer myself liking people to myself loving mankind.

01:57:43.920 --> 01:57:47.200
[Guest]: I prefer keeping a needle and thread on hand just in case.

01:57:47.920 --> 01:57:49.120
[Guest]: I prefer the color green.

01:57:49.120 --> 01:57:52.960
[Guest]: I prefer not to maintain that reason is to blame for everything.

01:57:53.600 --> 01:57:54.880
[Guest]: I prefer exceptions.

01:57:54.880 --> 01:57:56.160
[Guest]: I prefer to leave early.

01:57:56.960 --> 01:58:00.000
[Guest]: I prefer the old fine line illustrations.

01:58:00.000 --> 01:58:04.640
[Guest]: I prefer the absurdity of writing poems to the absurdity of not writing poems.

01:58:05.200 --> 01:58:10.880
[Guest]: I prefer where love's concerned, non-specific anniversaries that can be celebrated every day.

01:58:11.920 --> 01:58:15.200
[Guest]: I prefer cunning kindness to the over-trustful kind.

01:58:15.920 --> 01:58:18.720
[Guest]: I prefer conquered to conquering countries.

01:58:19.280 --> 01:58:21.200
[Guest]: I prefer having some reservations.

01:58:21.760 --> 01:58:25.120
[Guest]: I prefer Grimm's fairy tales to the newspaper's front pages.

01:58:25.120 --> 01:58:29.360
[Guest]: I prefer leaves without flowers to flowers without leaves.

01:58:29.920 --> 01:58:32.480
[Guest]: I prefer dogs with uncropped tails.

01:58:33.120 --> 01:58:35.760
[Guest]: I prefer light eyes since mine are dark.

01:58:36.480 --> 01:58:41.600
[Guest]: I prefer many things that I haven't mentioned here to many things I've also left unsaid.

01:58:42.880 --> 01:58:47.040
[Guest]: I prefer zeros on the loose to those lined up behind a cipher.

01:58:48.000 --> 01:58:50.800
[Guest]: I prefer the time of insects to the time of stars.

01:58:51.600 --> 01:58:53.040
[Guest]: I prefer to knock on wood.

01:58:53.040 --> 01:58:55.920
[Guest]: I prefer not to ask how much longer and when.

01:58:56.720 --> 01:59:02.000
[Guest]: I prefer keeping in mind even the possibility that existence has its own reason for being.

01:59:02.960 --> 01:59:04.000
[Guest]: Just stunning.

01:59:04.000 --> 01:59:05.120
[Guest]: She's so good.

01:59:05.120 --> 01:59:05.920
[Guest]: That's just stunning.

01:59:05.920 --> 01:59:06.640
[Guest]: She's so good.

01:59:06.640 --> 01:59:08.960
[Guest]: And to think that she writes in Polish.

01:59:08.960 --> 01:59:09.520
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:59:09.520 --> 01:59:10.080
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:59:10.080 --> 01:59:11.920
[Guest]: And the translation is wonderful.

01:59:12.480 --> 01:59:16.560
[Amit Varma]: And translation is another fine art by itself because the languages are just so inherently

01:59:16.560 --> 01:59:17.120
[Amit Varma]: different.

01:59:17.120 --> 01:59:18.720
[Amit Varma]: Just thought of, you know.

01:59:18.720 --> 01:59:20.240
[Amit Varma]: And to find that word.

01:59:20.240 --> 01:59:23.120
[Guest]: Yeah, and that phrase that will connect with the reader.

01:59:23.120 --> 01:59:28.560
[Amit Varma]: Or more so just the essence of something like, and that's something I've often wondered about

01:59:28.560 --> 01:59:30.960
[Amit Varma]: that languages have their own inherent qualities.

01:59:30.960 --> 01:59:35.600
[Amit Varma]: For example, like I mentioned earlier, I think most Japanese writers I read tend to be quite

01:59:35.600 --> 01:59:38.240
[Amit Varma]: minimal and sparse and perhaps that's a quality in the language.

01:59:38.240 --> 01:59:44.880
[Amit Varma]: But equally, a lot of the Urdu shairi I love is so overflown and, you know, expressionistic.

01:59:44.880 --> 01:59:48.400
[Amit Varma]: And the thing is, if you translate them literally, they read like shit.

01:59:48.400 --> 01:59:48.960
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:59:48.960 --> 01:59:50.960
[Unknown]: That's true.

01:59:50.960 --> 01:59:55.280
[Amit Varma]: In English, they're like shit, because we are attaching a different set, not a better

01:59:55.280 --> 01:59:57.280
[Amit Varma]: set, but a different set of values to it.

01:59:57.280 --> 01:59:57.920
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:59:57.920 --> 01:59:58.480
[Guest]: A different set of heuristics.

01:59:58.480 --> 01:59:59.280
[Guest]: Completely agree.

01:59:59.280 --> 02:00:02.960
[Guest]: Like, I never want fairs to be translated in English ever.

02:00:02.960 --> 02:00:06.080
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, because it'll be like, what just kind of...

02:00:06.080 --> 02:00:07.920
[Guest]: I'll never read him in English.

02:00:07.920 --> 02:00:10.000
[Guest]: Can never think of it in English.

02:00:10.000 --> 02:00:10.240
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:00:10.240 --> 02:00:12.800
[Guest]: Or Mir or anyone for that matter.

02:00:12.800 --> 02:00:13.600
[Unknown]: Amrita Pritam.

02:00:14.320 --> 02:00:15.120
[Guest]: Never, can never.

02:00:15.120 --> 02:00:18.160
[Guest]: From Punjabi to English, it just wouldn't make sense.

02:00:18.160 --> 02:00:18.960
[Unknown]: Yeah.

02:00:18.960 --> 02:00:22.480
[Guest]: If somebody tried to translate meh tenu phir milangi, it was a disaster.

02:00:23.040 --> 02:00:25.200
[Amit Varma]: I was like, don't, don't even bother.

02:00:25.200 --> 02:00:26.400
[Amit Varma]: I shall meet you again.

02:00:26.400 --> 02:00:26.960
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:00:26.960 --> 02:00:27.520
[Amit Varma]: I'll be back.

02:00:27.520 --> 02:00:32.400
[Guest]: That was, I mean, that's basically Schwarzenegger saying meh tenu phir milangi milanga.

02:00:32.400 --> 02:00:34.640
[Guest]: Now there's a new Terminator movie.

02:00:34.640 --> 02:00:35.360
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:00:35.360 --> 02:00:38.160
[Amit Varma]: The Punjabi dubbed version should kindly have these.

02:00:40.320 --> 02:00:41.680
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, very true.

02:00:41.680 --> 02:00:43.760
[Guest]: I think we've reached the two hour mark.

02:00:43.760 --> 02:00:47.920
[Amit Varma]: So I'll finish off a poem and then we'll have some final words.

02:00:47.920 --> 02:00:50.720
[Amit Varma]: This one is a traditional rhyming type poetry.

02:00:50.720 --> 02:00:52.880
[Amit Varma]: So if you guys are wondering what the hell is happening here.

02:00:52.880 --> 02:00:54.080
[Amit Varma]: Rhyme kyu nahi karda?

02:00:54.080 --> 02:00:54.640
[Amit Varma]: This one.

02:00:54.640 --> 02:00:55.360
[Amit Varma]: Rhyme karda.

02:00:56.320 --> 02:00:59.600
[Amit Varma]: This is called A Long Distance Too by Tony Harrison.

02:00:59.600 --> 02:01:00.160
[Unknown]: Have you?

02:01:00.160 --> 02:01:00.880
[Unknown]: No.

02:01:00.880 --> 02:01:02.640
[Amit Varma]: Long Distance Too by Tony Harrison.

02:01:03.920 --> 02:01:08.960
[Amit Varma]: Though my mother was already two years dead, dad kept her slippers warming by the gas,

02:01:08.960 --> 02:01:13.280
[Amit Varma]: put hot water bottles aside of the bed and still went to renew her transport pass.

02:01:13.920 --> 02:01:16.240
[Amit Varma]: You couldn't just drop in, you had to phone.

02:01:16.240 --> 02:01:21.120
[Amit Varma]: He'd put you off an hour to give him time to clear away her things and look alone,

02:01:21.120 --> 02:01:23.440
[Amit Varma]: as though his still raw love was such a crime.

02:01:24.000 --> 02:01:29.200
[Amit Varma]: He couldn't risk my blight of disbelief, though sure that very soon he'd hear her key,

02:01:29.200 --> 02:01:31.360
[Amit Varma]: scrape in the rusted lock and end his grief.

02:01:31.920 --> 02:01:34.320
[Amit Varma]: He knew she'd just popped out to get the tea.

02:01:34.960 --> 02:01:37.600
[Amit Varma]: I believe life ends with death and that is all.

02:01:37.600 --> 02:01:39.200
[Amit Varma]: You haven't both gone shopping.

02:01:39.200 --> 02:01:39.840
[Amit Varma]: Just the same.

02:01:40.480 --> 02:01:44.960
[Amit Varma]: In my new black leather phone book, there's your name and the disconnected number I still call.

02:01:44.960 --> 02:01:47.520
[Amit Varma]: Wow, lovely.

02:01:47.520 --> 02:01:48.320
[Unknown]: It's so good.

02:01:48.320 --> 02:01:51.680
[Amit Varma]: And if you see it on the page, it's very interesting what he's done here.

02:01:51.680 --> 02:01:54.720
[Amit Varma]: If you see it on the page, it's got four stanzas.

02:01:54.720 --> 02:01:59.600
[Amit Varma]: The first three have this rhyme scheme of ABAB and the last one is ABBA.

02:02:00.480 --> 02:02:05.840
[Amit Varma]: And that actually makes a sort of difference in just the effect that the poem has.

02:02:06.800 --> 02:02:08.400
[Guest]: It just touches, that's all.

02:02:08.400 --> 02:02:09.680
[Guest]: Yeah, very moving.

02:02:09.680 --> 02:02:13.360
[Guest]: I don't know if you, Brian Patton, I don't know if you've heard of him.

02:02:13.360 --> 02:02:15.040
[Amit Varma]: Wasn't he?

02:02:15.040 --> 02:02:17.920
[Amit Varma]: No, no, Chris Patton was in charge of Hong Kong when they handed over.

02:02:18.880 --> 02:02:21.600
[Guest]: Brian Patton writes poetry just like this.

02:02:21.600 --> 02:02:22.400
[Guest]: It's just beautiful.

02:02:23.280 --> 02:02:24.560
[Guest]: Very, very touching.

02:02:25.280 --> 02:02:25.920
[Guest]: Very soft.

02:02:26.800 --> 02:02:34.000
[Guest]: I find, you know, in poetry, which is so strange, I find male poets also to have that sense of

02:02:34.000 --> 02:02:36.720
[Guest]: softness sometimes, most of the time.

02:02:36.720 --> 02:02:38.080
[Guest]: They're not harsh.

02:02:38.080 --> 02:02:44.000
[Guest]: Like when that happens a lot, I find that in prose, when it comes to men who write,

02:02:44.640 --> 02:02:50.160
[Guest]: I find that prose sometimes very jarring, like Richard Ford.

02:02:50.800 --> 02:02:56.640
[Guest]: I don't find him making a point softly, like Murakami will make a point softly.

02:02:57.680 --> 02:03:02.480
[Guest]: So I think maybe because of the culture, maybe, I don't know, it'll be very interesting to

02:03:02.480 --> 02:03:03.280
[Guest]: find out why.

02:03:03.280 --> 02:03:05.520
[Amit Varma]: But have you read Mary Oliver's poetry?

02:03:05.520 --> 02:03:06.160
[Amit Varma]: Yes.

02:03:06.160 --> 02:03:10.160
[Amit Varma]: And have you read this wonderful book, which I recommend all my listeners go out and just

02:03:10.160 --> 02:03:11.920
[Amit Varma]: buy right now, blindly, just trust me.

02:03:12.480 --> 02:03:14.480
[Amit Varma]: But it is called a Poetry Handbook.

02:03:14.480 --> 02:03:15.200
[Amit Varma]: By her only.

02:03:15.200 --> 02:03:16.000
[Guest]: By Mary Oliver.

02:03:16.000 --> 02:03:16.480
[Guest]: Yes.

02:03:16.480 --> 02:03:21.600
[Amit Varma]: Where she talks about, I mean, that got me to appreciate poetry so much more just in

02:03:21.600 --> 02:03:24.720
[Amit Varma]: terms of how poets do their thing and.

02:03:24.720 --> 02:03:26.960
[Guest]: The style and the craft more than anything.

02:03:27.680 --> 02:03:31.440
[Guest]: Even this lady, Anne Lamott, if I'm not mistaken.

02:03:32.400 --> 02:03:35.760
[Guest]: Isn't it the lady who wrote the book called One Bird at a Time?

02:03:35.760 --> 02:03:36.400
[Guest]: Bird by Bird.

02:03:36.400 --> 02:03:38.560
[Guest]: Just Bird by Bird.

02:03:38.560 --> 02:03:40.000
[Guest]: That's on the craft of writing.

02:03:40.000 --> 02:03:43.360
[Amit Varma]: Which is on the craft of writing, which is a lovely story.

02:03:43.360 --> 02:03:50.080
[Amit Varma]: I mean, the story that from which the book gets its title is that when they were kids,

02:03:50.080 --> 02:03:53.440
[Amit Varma]: she and her little brother, they were with the family at a summer cabin.

02:03:53.440 --> 02:03:58.160
[Amit Varma]: And by the time the vacation got over, the kid had to do this sort of homework project

02:03:58.160 --> 02:04:04.080
[Amit Varma]: where he had to, I think, describe birds or paste pictures of birds on a scrapbook or

02:04:04.080 --> 02:04:07.360
[Amit Varma]: whatever by the end of the holiday, and they had ample time to do it.

02:04:07.360 --> 02:04:12.560
[Amit Varma]: But like all of us who face deadlines and react to them the same way as they go, Wu Xing Bai,

02:04:12.560 --> 02:04:14.880
[Amit Varma]: he basically left it for the very last day.

02:04:14.880 --> 02:04:18.960
[Amit Varma]: And then the little kid had a near panic attack on the last day because there were so many

02:04:18.960 --> 02:04:19.360
[Amit Varma]: birds.

02:04:19.360 --> 02:04:23.040
[Amit Varma]: And her dad told him just do it, Bird by Bird.

02:04:23.040 --> 02:04:23.540
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:04:24.160 --> 02:04:25.440
[Amit Varma]: And that was it.

02:04:25.440 --> 02:04:31.200
[Amit Varma]: And in that vein, I hope that Bird by Bird, you shall also get to your next book and to

02:04:31.200 --> 02:04:32.000
[Amit Varma]: many more books.

02:04:32.000 --> 02:04:32.880
[Guest]: Thank you so much for coming on the show.

02:04:32.880 --> 02:04:34.160
[Guest]: Thank you so much for inviting me.

02:04:34.160 --> 02:04:35.120
[Guest]: It was a pleasure.

02:04:35.120 --> 02:05:03.120
[Amit Varma]: Thanks a lot.

02:05:05.120 --> 02:05:15.120
[Amit Varma]: Thank you.

02:05:35.120 --> 02:05:49.120
[Unknown]: Thank you.

02:06:05.120 --> 02:06:17.120
[Unknown]: Thank you.

02:06:35.120 --> 02:06:45.120
[Unknown]: Thank you.

